Name: Aahotepre
Comment: A pharaoh of Canaanite descent from the 14th Dynasty possibly identical to 'Ammu.

Name: Aat
Comment: Queen and wife of Amenemhat III.

Name: Abar
Comment: An Egyptian queen, the mother of King Taharqa and probably the wife of King Piye.

Name: Achillas
Comment: Commander under the Ptolemaic Egyptian king Ptolemy XIII. Executed at the orders of Arsinoe IV of Egypt by Ganymedes.

Name: Addaya
Comment: Egyptian commissioner in southern Canaan mentioned in the Amarna letters. He probably served under Pharaohs Amenhotep III and/or Akhenaten.

Name: Agathoclea
Comment: Mistress of the Ptolemaic king Ptolemy IV Philopator and sister of his chief minister, Agathocles. Together, they managed to achieve complete influence over Ptolemy IV.

Name: Agathocles
Comment: Chief minister of the Ptolemaic king Ptolemy IV Philopator and brother of the king's mistress Agathoclea. Together, they managed to achieve complete influence over Ptolemy IV.

Name: Ahaneith
Comment: Wife of King Djet

Name: Ahhotep I
Comment: A daughter of Queen Tetisheri and Senakhtenre Ahmose, and was probably the sister, as well as the wife, of pharaoh Seqenenre Tao. Ahhotep reigned as regent until her son, Ahmose I, was of age. Also known as Ahhotpe or Aahhotep.

Name: Ahhotep II
Comment: Probably the Great Royal Wife of pharaoh Kamose.

Name: Ahmes
Comment: He wrote the Rhind Mathematical Papyrus, a work of Ancient Egyptian mathematics. Also called Ahmose.

Name: Senakhtenre Ahmose
Comment: Pharaoh of the late 17th dynasty, his existence and complete name were confirmed by recent archeological discoveries.

Name: Ahmose I
Comment: Founder of the 18th dynasty. He was a son of pharaoh Seqenenre Tao and brother of the last pharaoh of the seventeenth dynasty, Kamose. During his reign, he completed the conquest and expulsion of the Hyksos from the delta region and restored Theban rule over the whole of Egypt.

Name: Ahmose
Comment: A daughter of pharaoh Seqenenre Tao by his sister-wife Sitdjehuti. Ahmose was a half-sister of Pharaoh Ahmose I.

Name: Ahmose
Comment: Wife of 18th dynasty pharaoh, Thutmose I, and the mother of queen and later, pharaoh, Hatshepsut.

Name: Ahmose
Main Title:
King's son
High Priest of Re
Comment: Probably a son of pharaoh Amenhotep II. He was in office as High Priest of Re in Heliopolis during the reign of his brother Thutmose IV.

Name: Ahmose, son of Ebana
Date: (fl. c. mid to late-16th century BC)
Comment: Served in the Egyptian military under the 17th and 18th dynasty pharaohs Seqenenre Tao, Ahmose I, Amenhotep I, and Thutmose I.

Name: Ahmose-ankh
Comment: A son of Pharaoh Ahmose I and queen Ahmose Nefertari. He was the crown prince but pre-deceased his father.

Name: Ahmose-Henutemipet
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Seqenenre Tao and probably Queen Ahhotep I. She was the sister of Ahmose I.

Name: Ahmose-Henuttamehu
Comment: Daughter of 17th dynasty pharaoh Seqenenre Tao by his sister-wife Ahmose-Inhapi. She was probably married to her half-brother Pharaoh Ahmose I. Ahmose-Henuttamehu was a half-sister to Queen Ahmose-Nefertari.

Name: Ahmose-Inhapi
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Senakhtenre Ahmose and was sister to Pharaoh Seqenenre Tao, and the queens Ahhotep I and Sitdjehuti. She was married to her (half-)brother Seqenenre Tao and they had a daughter, Ahmose-Henuttamehu.

Name: Ahmose-Meritamon
Comment: She was probably a daughter of Seqenenre Tao. Her mummy was found in the Deir el-Bahri cache and is now in the Egyptian Museum in Cairo.

Name: Ahmose-Meritamun
Comment: Daughter of Ahmose I and Ahmose Nefertari, and was queen of her brother Amenhotep I.

Name: Ahmose-Nebetta
Comment: Probably the daughter of Seqenenre Tao and a sister of Ahmose I.

Name: Ahmose Nefertari
Date: (fl. c. mid to late-16th century BC)
Comment: A daughter of Seqenenre Tao and Ahhotep I, and royal sister and the wife of pharaoh Ahmose I. Following Ahmose I's death, Ahmose-Nefertari became the regent for her son Amenhotep I and ruled until he was old enough to rule on his own.

Name: Ahmose Pen-Nekhebet
Date: (fl. c. late-16th to early-15th century BC)
Comment: An Egyptian official and military commander who started his career under Ahmose I and served all subsequent pharaohs until Thutmose III.

Name: Ahmose Sapair
Comment: Probably a son of Pharaoh Seqenenre Tao and a brother of Ahmose I.

Name: Ahmose-Sitamun
Comment: The daughter of Pharaoh Ahmose I and sister of Amenhotep I. A colossal statue of hers stood before the eighth pylon at Karnak.

Name: Ahmose called Si-Tayit
Comment: Viceroy of Kush during the reign of Ahmose I. Possibly the first Viceroy to serve in that capacity. Early in the reign of Amenhotep I, the position passed from Si-Tayit to his son Ahmose called Turo.

Name: Ahmose-Sitkamose
Comment: Probably the daughter of Pharaoh Kamose. She probably married Ahmose I. Also called Sitkamose.

Name: Ahmose-Tumerisy
Comment: Probably a daughter of pharaoh Seqenenre Tao and a sister of Ahmose I.

Name: Ahmose called Turo
Comment: Viceroy of Kush under Amenhotep I and Tuthmosis I. Son of Ahmose called Si-Tayit.

Name: Akhenaten
Comment: Was known before the 5th year of his reign as Amenhotep IV (or Amenophis IV). He abandoned traditional Egyptian polytheism and introducing worship centered on Aten. Also called Echnaton or Akhenaton.

Name: Akhraten
Comment: Possibly a son of Harsiotef and a brother of Nastasen. Akhraten may have been succeeded by Nastasen.

Name: Alara of Nubia
Comment: The founder of the Napatan royal dynasty and was the first recorded prince of Nubia. He unified all of Upper Nubia from Meroë to the Third Cataract. His successors would comprise the 25th Dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Alexander Helios
Comment: Eldest son of queen Cleopatra VII and Roman triumvir Mark Antony.

Name: Amanibakhi
Comment: Kushite King of Meroe. The successor of Akhraten and the predecessor of Nastasen.

Name: Amanineteyerike
Comment: Kushite King of Meroe. The son of King Malewiebamani, and brother of Baskakeren. His predecessor Talakhamani was either an older brother or an uncle. His name is also written as Amanneteyerike, Aman-nete-yerike, or Irike-Amannote.

Name: Amasis II
Comment: Based at Sais and the successor to Apries. Under Amasis II, Egypt's agricultural based economy reached its zenith. He was able to defeat an invasion of Egypt by the Babylonian king Nebuchadrezzar II. Also called Ahmose II.

Name: Amenemhat I
Comment: The first ruler of the 12th dynasty. Amenemhat I was a vizier of his predecessor Mentuhotep IV. He moved the capital from Thebes to Itjtawy.

Name: Amenemhat II
Comment: The third pharaoh of the 12th dynasty of Egypt. He was the son of Senusret I through the latter's chief wife, Queen Neferu III.

Name: Amenemhat III
Comment: Sixth king of the 12th dynasty. Son of Senusret III.

Name: Amenemhat IV
Comment: Seventh king of the 12th dynasty. Possibly a son of Amenemhat III.

Name: Amenemhat V Sekhemkare
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th Dynasty. He appears as 'Sekhemkare' in the Turin King List.

Name: Amenemhet VI
Comment: The seventh king of the Thirteenth Dynasty according to the Turin Canon.

Name: Amenemhat
Comment: Also known as Ameny, a governor at Men'at Khufu during the reign of pharaoh Senusret I.

Name: Amenemhat
Comment: High Priest of Amun during the reign of pharaoh Amenhotep II.

Name: Amenemhat
Comment: Son of Pharaoh Thutmose III. He was the eldest son and appointed heir but predeceased his father.

Name: Amenemhat
Comment: The son of Pharaoh Thutmose IV. He died young and was buried in his father's tomb.

Name: Amenemhatankh
Comment: A son of Amenemhat II.

Name: Amenemipet called Pairy
Comment: He served during the reigns of Amenhotep II and Thutmose IV.

Name: Amenemnisu
Comment: Second pharaoh of the 21st dynasty. Only ruled 4 years.

Name: Amenemope
Comment: The son of Psusennes I and Queen Mutnedjemet. He was the successor to his father, and after c. 9 years of rule, he was succeeded by Osorkon the Elder. AMenemope was buried in Tanis.

Name: Amenemopet
Comment: He was probably a son of Amenhotep II. Known from stela from Giza, and possibly depicted on the stela of the royal nurse Senetruiu.

Name: Amenemopet
Comment: She was probably a daughter of Thutmose IV. Buried with other royal princesses in the Sheikh Abd el-Qurna cache.

Name: Amenemopet
Comment: Served as Viceroy of Kush during the reign of the 19th dynasty pharaoh Seti I.

Name: Amenemope
Comment: Amenemope, son of Kanakht, is thought to be the author of the Instruction of Amenemope, an Egyptian text written in the Ramesside Period. His discourses are presented in the traditional form of instructions from father to son on how to live a good and moral life.

Name: Amenhotep I
Comment: The second pharaoh of the 18th dynasty of Egypt. He was the son of Ahmose I and queen Ahmose-Nefertari. He inherited an enlarged kingdom formed by his father's military conquests and maintained dominance over Nubia and the Nile Delta. Also called Amenophis I'.

Name: Amenhotep II
Comment: The son of Thutmose III and Queen Merytre-Hatshepsut. Also called Amenophis II'.

Name: Amenhotep III
Comment: The son of Thutmose IV and queen Mutemwia. His lengthy reign was a period of unprecedented prosperity and artistic splendour, when Egypt reached the peak of her artistic and international power. Also called Amenophis III'.

Name: Amenhotep IV
Comment: Son of Amenhotep III and Queen Tiye. Changed his name to Akhenaten in the 4th year of his reign.

Name: Amenhotep, son of Hapu
Comment: Amenhotep, son of Hapu, was an architect, a priest, a scribe, and a public official, who held a number of offices under Pharaoh Amenhotep III.

Name: Amenhotep
Comment: A High Priest in the Temple of Amun.

Name: Amenhotep
Comment: High priest of Amun under the 20th dynasty pharaohs Ramesses IX to Ramesses XI. He was also the vizier and first prophet of Amun-resonther.

Name: Amenhotep
Comment: A son and possibly the designated heir of Amenhotep II.

Name: Amenhotep Huy
Comment: Amenhotep-Huy was the high steward of Memphis under Amenhotep III. He was one of the highest officials at the royal court.

Name: Amenhotep-Huy
Comment: He served during the reign of the 18th dynasty pharaoh Amenhotep III. He was also director of Upper and Lower Egypt and overseer of all the works of the King in Upper and Lower Egypt.

Name: Amenia
Comment: The first wife of the pharaoh Horemheb, the last ruler of the 18th dynasty. Amenia died before Horemheb became Pharaoh. Buried in Saqqara.

Name: Amenirdis I Khaneferumut
Comment: She was a Kushite princess, daughter of Pharaoh Kashta and Queen Pebatjma.

Name: Amenirdis II
Comment: A daughter of the Kushite pharaoh Taharqa and was adopted by Shepenupet II, daughter of Piye, to become Divine Adoratrice of Amun.

Name: Amenmesse
Comment: Possibly the son of Pharaoh Merneptah and Queen Takhat. Amenmesse likely usurped the throne from Seti II, Merneptah's son. The two may have ruled as rivals until Seti II defeated Amenmesse. Also called Amenmesses or Amenmose.

Name: Amenmose
Comment: He was an Egyptian noble who lived during the reigns of the Pharaohs Thutmose III and Amenhotep II.

Name: Amenmose
Comment: The eldest son and designated heir of Thutmose I. He predeceased his father.

Name: Amenmose
Comment: Vizier of Egypt during the reigns of the Pharaohs Amenmesse and Seti II.

Name: Amethu called Ahmose
Comment: He held this position during the reigns of the Pharaohs Thutmose II and Hatshepsut and during the early years of the reign of Thutmose III.

Name: Ameny Qemau
Comment: Ameny Qemau ruled during the early 13th dynasty. A pyramid in southern Dahshur was constructed for him. Possibly also known as Sehotepibre.

Name: Ammeris
Comment: A vassal of Shabaka of the 25th dynasty, installed as governor of Sais by him.

Name: Amun-her-khepeshef
Comment: The first-born son of the 19th dynasty Pharaoh Ramesses II and Queen Nefertari. He was the crown prince of Egypt but predeceased his father. His name is also written as Amonhirkhopshef and earlier in his life as Amun-her-wenemef.

Name: Amun-her-khepeshef
Comment: The eldest son and appointed heir of the 20th dynasty Pharaoh Ramesses III.

Name: Amyrtaeus
Comment: The only king of the 28th dynasty of Egypt who ruled after the first Persian occupation of Egypt. Amyrtaeus started a revolt against Darius II of Persia in 411 BC and following the death of Darius declared himself king. Amyrtaeus was defeated in a battle with his successor, Nepherites I of Mendes, and executed. Also known as Amenirdisu of Sais.

Name: Analmaye
Comment: He succeeded King Malonaqen and was in turn succeeded by King Amaninatakilebte.

Name: Anat-her
Dynasty: 15th or 16th dynasty or contemporaneous with 12th dynasty
Date: (fl. c. late-19th to mid-17th century BC)
Comment: Obscur semitic ruler during the second intermediate period. Possibly a vassal of the Hyksos, a Hyksos prince, or a Canaanite chieftain contemporaneous with the 12th dynasty.

Name: Anedjib
Comment: Possibly a son of King Den.

Name: Anen
Comment: Anen was the brother of Queen Tiye, the wife of Amenhotep III.

Name: Anhotep
Comment: Viceroy of Kush during the reign of Ramesses II.

Name: Ankh-ef-en-Khonsu i
Comment: He is best known under the name of Ankh-af-na-khonsu, and as the dedicant of the so-called Stela of Revealing

Name: Ankhefensekhmet
Comment: He probably served during the reigns of king Psusennes II and king Shoshenq I.

Name: Ankherfenedjef
Comment: He was a son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu, and of Itet.

Name: Ankhesenamen
Comment: Named Ankhesenpaaten at her birth, she was a daughter of the Egyptian Pharaoh Akhenaten and Nefertiti and became queen to her (half-) brother Tutankhamun. Following their marriage, the couple honored the deities of the restored religion by changing their names to Tutankhamun and Ankhesenamen.

Name: Ankhesenpaaten Tasherit
Comment: She was probably the daughter of Ankhesenamun (who was named Ankhesenpaaten as a princess) and Akhenaten.

Name: Ankhesenpepi I
Comment: A queen consort to Pharaoh Pepi I. Ankhesenpepi was a daughter of Nebet, the female vizier, and her husband Khui. Also called Ankhenesmeryre I.

Name: Ankhesenpepi II
Comment: Ankhesenpepi was a daughter of Nebet, the female vizier, and her husband Khui. Ankhesenpepi II was married to Pharaoh Pepi I and later was a queen to Merenre Nemtyemsaf I. Also called Ankhenesmeryre II.

Name: Ankhesenpepi III
Comment: She was a daughter of Nemtyemsaf I and she became the wife of Pepi II.

Name: Ankhesenpepi IV
Comment: Queen of Pharaoh Pepi II. She was the mother of 7th dynasty king Neferkare II.

Name: Ankhhaf
Comment: An Egyptian prince who served as vizier and overseer of works for King Khafre. Ankhhaf was a son of pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Ankhkherednefer
Comment: He served under pharaoh Osorkon II. His name is also written as Ankhrenepnefer and Ankhsherynefer.

Name: Ankhmakis
Comment: He was the second king (reigned c.199 BC – c.185 BC) of a dynasty which controlled much of Upper Egypt during the reigns of the Egyptian kings Ptolemy IV and Ptolemy V. His name is also written as: Ankhonnophris, Khaonnophris, Chaonnophris and Ankmachis.

Name: Ankhmare
Comment: Son of King Khafre. Served as vizier.

Name: Ankhnesneferibre
Comment: Ankhnesneferibre was the daughter of Psamtik II and his wife Takhuit. She governed Thebes until the Persian conquest of Egypt in 525 BC.

Name: Ankhreshet
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu, and of Itet. His name is also written as Ankhersheretef.

Name: Ankhtifi
Comment: He was the nomarch of Hierakonpolis and a supporter of the Herakleopolitan-based 10th dynasty which was locked in conflict with the Theban-based 11th Dynasty kings for control of Egypt.

Name: Ankhu
Comment: He was vizier during the reigns of King Khendjer and King Sobekhotep II.

Name: Anlamani
Comment: During his reign, Kush experienced a revival in its power in the region.

Name: 'Apepi
Comment: Obscur pharaoh of Canaanite descent reigning in the late 14th Dynasty.

Name: Apepi
Comment: Penultimate Hyksos ruler of Lower and Middle Egypt, belonging to the 15th dynasty and reigning towards the end of the Second Intermediate Period. Also known as Ipepi or Apophis.

Name: Aperanat
Date: (fl. c. mid to late 17th century BC)
Comment: Semitic ruler of Lower Egypt, easier an early Hyksos king of the 15th Dynasty or a vassal of the Hyksos kings.

Name: Aperel
Comment: Also known as Aperia. He was a vizier of Egypt who served during the reigns of the 18th dynasty pharaohs Amenhotep III and Akhenaten.

Name: Apries Wahibre Haaibre
Comment: During his reign, a civil war broke out between Egyptian army troops and foreign mercenaries in the Egyptian army. Egyptians turned for support towards a victorious general, Amasis II, who declared himself pharaoh and Apries fled Egypt.

Name: Aramatle-qo
Comment: Also known as Amtalqa, he was a Nubian king who was the son and successor of King Aspelta and Queen Henuttakhbit.

Name: Aristomenes of Alyzia
Comment: Also known as Aristomenes the Acarnanian. He was regent and chief minister of Egypt in the Ptolemaic period during the reign of the boy king Ptolemy V. Around 196 BC, Ptolemy V took personal control of his kingdom, but Aristomenes remained chief minister until he was removed from power in 192 BC.

Name: Arsinoe I
Comment: First wife of Ptolemy II of Egypt. They had three children, including his successor Ptolemy III of Egypt. Around 274 BC, she was accused by Arsinoe II of plotting against him and went in exile.

Name: Arsinoe II
Comment: Queen of Thrace, Asia Minor and Macedonia and wife of King Lysimachus, her half-brother Ptolemy Keraunos and later co-ruler of Egypt with her brother and husband King Ptolemy II Philadelphus.

Name: Arsinoe III
Comment: She was a daughter of Ptolemy III and Berenice II. In 220 BC she married her brother, Ptolemy IV and became queen of Egypt. She reigned 220 BC – 204 BC. She was murdered in a palace coup, shortly after her husband's death.

Name: Arsinoe IV
Comment: A daughter of Ptolemy XII Auletes. Arsinoe IV was a half-sister of Cleopatra VII and Ptolemy XIII. When Julius Caesar arrived in Alexandria in 48 BC and sided with Cleopatra VII, Arsinoe escaped from Alexandria but was later captured and taken to Rome. She lived in a temple in Ephesus until Cleopatra VIII arranged for Mark Antony to have her murdered.

Name: Artakama
Comment: The second wife of Ptolemy I Soter. Artakama married Ptolemy (then a general) in April 324 BC at the Susa marriage festival as ordered by Alexander the Great.

Name: Ashakhet I
Comment: Served as high priest during the reigns of Amenemnisu and possibly Psusennes I.

Name: Ashakhet II
Comment: He served during the reigns of King Siamun and King Psusennes II.

Name: Aspelta
Comment: A ruler of the kingdom of Kush. Egyptian forces invaded Kush because Pharaoh Psamtik II saw Aspelta as a threat to his authority over Upper Egypt. The capital, Napata, was sacked so Aspelta moved the Nubian capital to Meroë.

Name: Atakhebasken
Comment: Also known as Akhetbasaken. She was the queen consort to pharaoh Taharqa.

Name: Atlanersa
Comment: A Nubian king who was the successor of Tantamani, the last ruler of the 25th Nubian dynasty in Egypt. In contrast to his predecessor, Atlanersa's kingdom was restricted to the region of Kush south of Aswan.

Name: Ay Kheperkheprure
Comment: The penultimate pharaoh of Egypt's 18th dynasty. He was pharaoh for a brief period, although he was a close advisor to two or three of the pharaohs who reigned before him and was the power behind the throne during Tutankhamun's reign.

Name: (Queen)
Comment: Possibly the wife of the 13th dynasty king Sobekhotep II.

Name: Babaef
Comment: Also known as Khnumbaf. He was a vizier during the reign of king Shepseskaf. He was probably the son of the vizier Duaenre.

Name: Bakenkhonsu
Comment: From the time of pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Bakenranef
Comment: Also known as Bocchoris. Was briefly a king of the 24th dynasty of Egypt. Based at Sais in the western Delta. Captured and executed by Shabaka, a king of the 25th dynasty.

Name: Bakenrenef
Comment: From the time of pharaoh Psamtik I.

Name: Baketwernel
Comment: Great Royal Wife of Ramesses IX.

Name: Baqet III
Comment: From the time of pharaoh Mentuhotep II.

Name: Baskakeren
Comment: King of Kush (reigned c. 405 BC – c. 404 BC) and was probably a son of King Malewiebamani and the younger brother of King Amanineteyerike. He succeeded Amanineteyerike to the throne.

Name: Baufra
Comment: Also known as Baufre or Bauefre. Baufra was a son of Pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Bay Irsu
Comment: Served under pharaoh Seti II and later became an influential powerbroker in the closing stages of the 19th dynasty. Executed.

Name: Bebi
Comment: Egyptian vizier under king Mentuhotep II.

Name: Bebiankh
Comment: Also known as Seuserenre Bebiankh. The successor of king Semenre.

Name: Bebnum
Date: fl. c. early to mid 17th century BC
Comment: Obscur ruler of Lower or Upper Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period. Only known from the Turin King List.

Name: Behenu
Comment: She is thought to have been the wife of either Pepi I or of Pepi II.

Name: Bek
Comment: Chief royal sculptor during the reign of Pharaoh Akhenaten. Bek followed the king to Akhetaten, the city founded by Akhenaten. He oversaw the construction of the great temple statues of the king.

Name: Beketamun
Comment: Also known as Beket. A daughter of Pharaoh Thutmose III.

Name: Beketaten
Comment: She was the youngest daughter of Pharaoh Amenhotep III and Tiye and thus the sister of Pharaoh Akhenaten.

Name: Benerib
Comment: Benerib was most likely a wife of pharaoh Hor-Aha, but she was not the mother of his heir, Djer.

Name: Berenice
Comment: Also known as Berenice Syra. Daughter of the Egyptian king Ptolemy II Philadelphus and Arsinoe I. She married the Seleucid monarch Antiochus II Theos who divorced his wife, Laodice I. When Antiochus II died, Berenice claimed the regency for her son, Seleucus. However, both Berenice and her son were then killed by Laodice I.

Name: Berenice I
Comment: A Macedonian noblewoman who, through her marriage to Ptolemy I Soter, became the first queen of the Ptolemaic dynasty of Egypt. Berenice travelled to Egypt as a lady-in-waiting to Eurydice, Ptolemy I's wife. Ptolemy I married Berenice in 317 BC.

Name: Berenice II
Comment: The daughter of Magas of Cyrene and Queen Apama II. Her husband, Demetrius the Fair, a Macedonian prince, moved to Cyrene where he became the lover of her mother Apama. So Berenice had him killed in Apama's bedroom. Afterwards she married the Egyptian king, Ptolemy III Euergetes.

Name: Berenice III
Comment: She ruled jointly with her uncle/husband Ptolemy X Alexander I (101 BC–88 BC). After Ptolemy X died, Ptolemy IX Lathyros reclaimed the throne, but when he died in 81 BC, Berenice took over the throne. The Roman Republic intervened and forced her to marry Ptolemy XI Alexander II, but he had her killed 19 days later.

Name: Berenice IV
Comment: Reigned 57 BC – 55 BC. She was a daughter of Ptolemy XII and Cleopatra V. After Cleopatra V's death, Berenice assumed the throne but was forced to marry Seleucus VII Kybiosaktes. So she had him murdered to remain sole ruler. After Ptolemy XII retook the throne with the aid of Roman soldiers, he had Berenice executed.

Name: Betrest
Comment: Betrest was the mother of the pharaoh Semerkhet.

Name: Bintanath
Comment: Also known as Bentanath. A daughter and later wife of the 19th dynasty Egyptian Pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Buneb
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Bunefer
Comment: Bunefer's titles as a priestess of Shepseskaf mean she may have been a wife or daughter of Shepseskaf or she was the wife of king Thamphthis.

Name: Caesarion
Comment: He was the last king of the Ptolemaic dynasty of Egypt (reigned 44 BC – 30 BC). He was the son of Cleopatra VII and Julius Caesar. He was killed on the orders of Octavian. Full name: Ptolemy XV Philopator Philometor Caesar.

Name: Charmian
Comment: A trusted servant and advisor to the historical Cleopatra VII of Egypt. Died with Cleopatra.

Name: Chephren
Comment: see Khafre

Name: Cheops
Comment: see Khufu

Name: Cleomenes of Naucratis
Comment: A Greek of Naucratis in Egypt, was appointed by Alexander III of Macedon as nomarch of the Arabian district of Egypt and receiver of the tributes from all the districts of Egypt and the neighboring part of Africa (331 BC).

Name: Cleopatra I Syra
Comment: Reigned 181 BC – 176 BC. She was the daughter of the Seleucid king Antiochus III and queen Laodice III. As part of a peace treaty, Antiochus III agreed to Cleopatra I marrying Ptolemy V (193 BC). Upon her Ptolemy V's death (181 BC), Cleopatra I ruled on behalf of her young son, Ptolemy VI.

Name: Cleopatra II
Comment: Reigned 169 BC – 145 BC, 130 BC – 127 BC, 124 BC – 116 BC. Cleopatra II was the daughter of Ptolemy V and Cleopatra I. She was the sister of, and later married, both Ptolemy VI (175 BC) and Ptolemy VIII (145 BC).

Name: Cleopatra III
Comment: Reigned 142 BC–131 BC and 127 BC – 101 BC. She was a daughter of Ptolemy VI and Cleopatra II. She married her uncle Ptolemy VIII. After the death of Ptolemy VIII (116 BC), Cleopatra III ruled with her eldest son Ptolemy IX and then with her second son Ptolemy X until Ptolemy X had her murdered.

Name: Cleopatra IV
Comment: Cleopatra IV was the daughter of Ptolemy VIII and Cleopatra III. Cleopatra IV married her brother Ptolemy IX (c.119 BC), and later the Seleucid prince, Antiochus IX Cyzicenus. Cleopatra IV was executed at the orders of Antiochus VIII.

Name: Cleopatra V Tryphaena
Comment: Cleopatra V was an illegitimate daughter of Ptolemy IX or a daughter of Ptolemy X. In 79 BC she married Ptolemy XII.

Name: Cleopatra VI Tryphaena
Comment: She was an older sister of Cleopatra VII and a daughter of Ptolemy XII and Cleopatra V.

Name: Cleopatra VII Philopator
Comment: Reigned 51 BC – 30 BC and mistress of Julius Caesar and Mark Antony. Cleopatra ruled jointly with her father Ptolemy XII and later with her brothers, Ptolemy XIII and Ptolemy XIV, whom she married. She had relationships with Julius Caesar and Mark Antony.

Name: Cleopatra Selene I
Comment: The daughter of the Egyptian king Ptolemy VIII and Cleopatra III. She was married to Ptolemy IX and later to the Seleucid kings, Antiochus VIII, Antiochus IX, and Antiochus X.

Name: Cleopatra Selene II
Comment: The only daughter of Cleopatra VII and Roman triumvir Mark Antony. She married King Juba II of Numidia. Sometimes called Cleopatra VIII.

Name: Cleopatra Thea
Comment: A daughter of Ptolemy VI of Egypt and Cleopatra II. She ruled Syria from 125 BC after the death of Demetrius II Nicator. She eventually ruled in co-regency with her son Antiochus VIII Grypus, who poisoned her in 121 or 120 BC.

Name: Dakhamunzu
Comment: Also called Dahamunzu. An Egyptian queen known from the Hittite annals The Deeds of Suppiluliuma, which were composed by Suppiluliuma I's son Mursili II. The identity of this queen has not yet been established with any degree of certainty and Dakhamunzu has variously been identified as either Nefertiti, Meritaten or Ankhesenamen.

Name: Dagi
Comment: An Egyptian vizier of the 11th dynasty during the reign of Mentuhotep II.

Name: Dedi
Comment: A soothsayer and magician in an Ancient Egyptian tale set in the era of Khufu, one of a number of stories to be found in the Westcar Papyrus.

Name: Dedumose I
Comment: A Pharaoh of Egypt during the 13th dynasty. Also known as Tutimaios.

Name: Dedumose II
Comment: A native Egyptian king of the 16th Theban dynasty during the Second Intermediate Period. His Horus name was Djedneferre.

Name: Demetrius the Fair
Comment: Reigned 250 BC – c. 249 BC. He was a son of King Demetrius I of Macedon and Ptolemais. When the Cyrenaean king Magas died in 250 BC, his widow, Apama II summoned Demetrius from Macedonia to become king of Cyrenaica and marry her daughter Berenice II. Shortly after his marriage to Berenice, Demetrius and Apama became lovers. In a jealous rage, Berenice killed Demetrius. Also known as Demetrius the Handsome.

Name: Den
Comment: He was the son of Queen Merneith. He was the first to use the title King of the Two Lands, and the first depicted as wearing the double crowns.

Name: Didia
Comment: High Priest of Ptah during the reign of the 19th dynasty pharaoh, Ramesses II. Didia succeeded his father Pahemnetjer into the office.

Name: Djaty
Comment: Djaty was a son of Queen Meresankh II and either pharaoh Djedefre or pharaoh Khafre. Also known as Djati, Zaty, Zati.

Name: Djau
Comment: He was a member of an influential family from Abydos; his mother was the vizier Nebet. His two sisters Ankhesenpepi I and Ankhesenpepi II married Pharaoh Pepi I.

Name: Djedefhor
Comment: He was a son of Pharaoh Khufu and brother of pharaohs Djedefre and Khafre. Also known as Hordjedef.

Name: Djedefptah
Comment: see Thamphthis

Name: Djedefre
Comment: He reigned c. 2566 BC – c. 2558 BC, the son and immediate successor of Khufu. Djedefre was the first king to use the title Son of Ra, which is seen as an indication of the growing popularity of the cult of the solar god Ra. Also known as Radjedef.

Name: Djedhor
Comment: He reigned 362–360 BC, the son and immediate successor of Nakhtnebef. Also known as Djedher, Takhos and Teos.

Name: Djedi
Comment: He was a son of Rahotep and Nofret and nephew of the pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Djediufankh
Comment: An ancient Egyptian priest who lived between 2,000 and 4,000 years ago.

Name: Djedkare Isesi
Comment: Built his pyramid at Saqqara instead of Abusir. Also referred to as Tancheres.

Name: Djedkare Shemai
Comment: A 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Djedkhonsuefankh
Comment: High Priest of Amun in Thebes. He was a son of Pinedjem I and succeeded his brother Masaherta during a time of great turmoil in the city of Thebes.

Name: Djedptahiufankh
Comment: Served as the 3rd or 4th Prophet of Amun and was the husband of Nestanebtishru (who was the daughter of Pinudjem II and Neskhons) during the reign of pharaoh Shoshenq.

Name: Djefatnebti
Comment: Probably a wife of the 3rd dynasty Egyptian king Huni.

Name: Djefatsen
Comment: A daughter of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Djehuti
Comment: An Egyptian pharaoh belonging to the Theban 16th dynasty based in Upper Egypt during the Second Intermediate period. Also called Djehuty Sekhemresementawy or Thuty.

Name: Djehutihotep
Comment: He is mainly known for the fine decorations on his tomb depicting how colossal statues were transported.

Name: Djehuty
Comment: A general under the Egyptian king Thutmosis III in the 18th dynasty. He led Egyptian forces in the capture of Joffa (modern Jaffa) in Canaan. Also referred to as Thuti or Thutii.

Name: Djehutyemhat
Comment: A local pharaoh at Hermopolis Magna, vassal of the 25th dynasty.

Name: Djehutynakht
Comment: Known for his large funerary equipment, exhibited at the Boston Museum of Fine Arts.

Name: Djer
Comment: The second or third pharaoh of the 1st dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Djeseretnebti
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Sekhemkhet from the 3rd dynasty. They were possibly the parents of pharaoh Khaba, Sekhemkhet's successor.

Name: Djet
Comment: An Egyptian pharaoh of the 1st dynasty. Also referred to as Wadj, Zet, and Uadji or Uenephes.

Name: Djoser
Comment: The best-known pharaoh of the 3rd dynasty of Egypt. He commissioned his official, Imhotep, to build the Step Pyramid for him at Saqqara. Also referred to as Netjerikhet, Tosarthros, Zoser, Dzoser, Zozer, Dsr, Djeser, Djésèr, Horus-Netjerikhet, and Horus-Netjerichet.

Name: Double Falcon
Comment: Predynastic ruler of Lower Egypt.

Name: Duaenhor
Comment: He was probably a son of Prince Kawab (son of Khufu) and Hetepheres II.

Name: Duaenre
Comment: Duaenre was the son of King Khafre and Queen Meresankh III.

Name: Duatentopet
Comment: The wife of Pharaoh Ramesses IV and mother of Ramesses V.

Name: Duathathor-Henuttawy
Comment: Probably the daughter of Ramesses XI, last king of the 20th dynasty, and queen Tentamun. She married Pinedjem I, the Theban High Priest of Amun who effectively ruled Upper Egypt during the reign of Ramesses XI.

Name: Eratosthenes
Comment: Eratosthenes was born in Cyrene (in modern-day Libya). He was the third chief librarian of the Great Library of Alexandria, the center of science and learning in the ancient world, and died in the capital of Ptolemaic Egypt.

Name: Euclid
Comment: A Greek mathematician, known as the "Father of Geometry". He was active in Alexandria during the reign of Ptolemy I. In his best-known work, Elements, Euclid deduced the principles of what is now called Euclidean geometry. Euclid also wrote on perspective, conic sections, spherical geometry, number theory, and rigor.

Name: Eurydice
Comment: A daughter of the Macedonian general Antipater and wife of Ptolemy, the son of Lagus, later Ptolemy I of Egypt. She married Ptolemy around 320 BC and was the mother of Ptolemy Keraunos, Meleager, Ptolemais and Lysandra.

Name: Ganymedes
Main Title: Tutor of Arsinoe IV, Military Commander
Comment: Tutor of Cleopatra VII's half-sister and rival, Arsinoë IV. During the civil war Ganymedes commanded Arsinoës' forces. In 47 BC Caesar won a decisive battle against Ganymedes who perished after fleeing the battle.

Name: Gautseshen
Comment: An Egyptian priestess, daughter of Menkheperre, High Priest of Amun. Her mother was Princess Isetemkheb, a daughter of Pharaoh Psusennes I.

Name: Gemenefkhonsbak
Comment: A local pharaoh at Tanis after the fall of the Tanite 22nd dynasty.

Name: Gilukhipa
Comment: A daughter of Shuttarna II, king of Mitanni. To assist with political relations between the two states, Gilukhipa was sent by Shuttarna II to Egypt to marry the 18th dynasty pharaoh Amenhotep III. Her name is sometimes written as Gilukhipa, Kilu-Hepa, or Kirgipa.

Name: Hakor
Comment: Hakor overthrew his predecessor Psammuthes. Hakor revolted against his overlord, the Persian King Artaxerxes, and with the support of Athenian mercenaries held off the Persians in a three-year war between 385 and 383 BC.

Name: Hannu
Comment: Served as m-r-pr "majordomus" under Mentuhotep II and Mentuhotep III.

Name: Hapuseneb
Comment: High priest from the time of Hatshepsut.

Name: Haremakhet
Comment: A son of Shabaka and High priest from the time of Tanutamani.

Name: Harkhebi
Comment: An astronomer who lived in Ptolemaic Egypt during the rule of the Ptolemaic dynasty.

Name: Harkhuf
Comment: Governor of Upper Egypt and overseer of caravans. His primary business was trade with Nubia, forging political bonds with local leaders and preparing the ground for an Egyptian expansion into Nubia. Also known as Herkhuf or Hirkhuf.

Name: Harsiese
Comment: He was a contemporary of Pharaoh Psusennes I.

Name: Harsiese Hedjkheperre Setepenamun
Comment: King of Thebes during the early years of the reign of 22nd dynasty pharaoh Osorkon II.

Name: Harsiese
Comment: A High Priest of Amun during the reigns of the pharaohs Osorkon II, Shoshenq III and Pedubast I.

Name: Harsiotef
Comment: A Kushite King of Meroe (reigned c. 404 BC – c. 369 BC). Harsiotef was probably the son of Queen Atasamale and King Amanineteyerike. His wives were Batahaliye and probably Pelkha.

Name: Harwa
Comment: Chief Steward of Amenirdis I. His tomb, TT37, is located in El-Assasif, part of the Theban Necropolis, on the West Bank of the Nile, opposite to Luxor.

Name: Hatshepsut
Comment: Wife of Tuthmose II. Served as regent for her stepson Tuthmose III and eventually had herself depicted as Pharaoh.

Name: Hatshepsut-Merytre
Comment: see Merytre-Hatshepsut

Name: Hedjetnebu
Comment: Her father was Pharaoh Djedkare. Also known as Hedjetnub.

Name: Hekenuhedjet
Comment: Wife of Pharaoh Khafre. Her son was the vizier Sekhemkare.

Name: Hemaka
Comment: An important official during the long reign of Pharaoh Den.

Name: Hemetre
Comment: She may have been a daughter or granddaughter of Khafre. She did not hold the title king's wife. She is mainly known from her tomb, which is located in the central field of Giza.

Name: Hemiunu
Comment: A son of Prince Nefermaat and his wife Itet. He is believed to be the architect of the Great Pyramid of Giza, Egypt.

Name: Henutmehyt
Comment: An Egyptian Theban priestess who lived during the 19th dynasty.

Name: Henutmire
Comment: A princess and queen, one of the eight wives of 19th dynasty pharaoh Ramesses II. Either a daughter or a younger sister of Ramesses II as well as his wife.

Name: Henutsen
Comment: She was a daughter of Pharaoh Sneferu and married her elder half-brother Khufu.

Name: Henuttaneb
Comment: A daughter of Egyptian 18th dynasty pharaoh Amenhotep III and Queen Tiye. She was a sister of Pharaoh Akhenaten.

Name: Henut Taui
Comment: A priestess and chantress of Amun at Thebes, mainly known for the alleged traces of cocaine and other New-World drugs on her mummy.

Name: Henuttawy
Comment: She was a daughter of Pharaoh Ramesses II and Queen Nefertari.

Name: Henuttawy
Comment: Her father was Pinedjem I, High Priest of Amun and de facto ruler of Southern Egypt and her mother was Duathathor-Henuttawy, a daughter of Ramesses XI.

Name: Henuttawy
Comment: A God's Wife of Amun during the 21st dynasty. Her father was Pinedjem II, High Priest of Amun and her mother was Isetemkheb, Singer of Amun.

Name: Henuttawy C
Comment: A Chantress of Amun during the 21st dynasty. Her father was Menkheperre, High Priest of Amun and her husband was Smendes II, High Priest of Amun.

Name: Henutwati
Comment: The Great Royal Wife of Ramesses V. Also known as Ta-Henutwati.

Name: Hepu
Comment: Hepu held office during the reign of Pharaoh Thutmose IV.

Name: Heqaib
Comment: He performed several successful expedition in the South under Pepi II. After his death Heqaib was promptly deified.

Name: Heqanakht
Comment: Viceroy of Kush during the reign of Ramesses II. His titles include: King's son of Kush, overseer of the Southern Lands, Fan-bearer on the king's right, Messenger to every land, etc.

Name: Herihor
Main Title: General, High Priest of Amun, Pharaoh
Comment: An Egyptian general and High Priest of Amun at Thebes during the reign of Ramesses XI. Herihor played an integral role in restoring order by ousting Pinehesy, viceroy of Nubia, from Thebes. He then assumed a number of titles, from high priest to vizier, before claiming to be pharaoh, although his power base remained limited to Thebes.

Name: Herneith
Comment: Queen consort to Djer.

Name: Hesy-Ra
Comment: Hersy-Ra was an official, physician and scribe who served under the pharaoh Djoser.

Name: Hetepheres
Comment: She was a daughter of pharaoh Sneferu and his half-sister, Queen Hetepheres I. Hetepheres married her younger half-brother Ankhhaf, who was a vizier.

Name: Hetepheres I
Comment: A daughter of pharaoh Huni, Hetepheres is considered to have been the wife of Sneferu. Hetepheres was the mother of Princess Hetepheres and King Khufu.

Name: Hetepheres II
Comment: A daughter of Khufu, during his reign she married her brother, the Crown Prince Kawab, with whom she had at least one child, a daughter named Meresankh III.

Name: Hetephernebti
Comment: The only known wife of Pharaoh Djoser.

Name: Hewernef
Comment: He served during the reign of the 20th dynasty pharaoh Ramesses III.

Name: Hor
Comment: Pharaoh of the 13th dynasty, also called Awibre, known for his intact tomb treasure, in particular his Ka-statue.

Name: Hor-Aha
Comment: Probably the second pharaoh of the 1st dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Horbaef
Comment: Horbaef was a son of Pharaoh Khufu. He married his half-sister Meresankh II and they had daughters named Nefertkau III and Nebty-tepites. Also known as Baefhor or Horbaf.

Name: Horemheb
Date: fl. c. late-14th to early-13th century BC
Comment: Last pharaoh of the 18th dynasty (reigned c. 1319 BC – c. 1292 BC). Before he became pharaoh, Horemheb was the commander in chief of the army for Tutankhamen and Ay and the legitimate heir of Tutankhamen. He appointed his vizier Paramesse as his successor, who would assume the throne as Ramesses I.

Name: Hori I
Comment: He served at the very end of the reign of the 19th dynasty pharaoh Ramesses II. Hori succeeded Neferronpet in office. Hori was a son of prince Khaemwaset and hence a grandson of Ramesses II.

Name: Hori I
Comment: Hori, son of Kama, was Viceroy of Kush under the 19th dynasty pharaoh Siptah. He continued to serve under the 20th dynasty pharaohs Setnakhte and Ramesses III.

Name: Hori II
Date: fl. c. early to mid-12th century BC
Comment: He served during the reigns of the 19th and 20th dynasty pharaohs Sethi II, Siptah, Tawosret, Setnakhte and Ramesses III. Hori II was the son of the High Priest of Ptah Hori I and the grandson of Prince Khaemweset.

Name: Hori II
Comment: Ason of the Viceroy of Kush, Hori I, and also served as Viceroy of Kush.

Name: Hornakht
Comment: A son of pharaoh Osorkon II. He was appointed by his father to the office of chief priest of Amun at Tanis to strengthen Osorkon's authority in Lower Egypt but Hornakht died at age 10.

Name: Horus Bird
Comment: Ephemeral ruler during the interregnum from the 1st to the 2nd dynasty

Name: Horus Sa
Comment: Enigmatic pharaoh reigning in the confused mid-2nd dynasty or in the 3rd dynasty.

Name: Hotepibre
Comment: Hotepibre Siharnedjheritef was likely a son of Ameny Qemau.

Name: Hotepsekhemwy
Comment: The first king of the 2nd dynasty of Egypt. (or Boethos)

Name: Hsekiu
Comment: Also known as Seka, was a Predynastic ancient Egyptian king who ruled in the Nile Delta.

Name: Hugronaphor
Comment: A Nubian noble who led Upper Egypt's secession from the rule of Ptolemy IV Philopator in 205 BC. His name is some times given as Hurganophor, Haronnophris, Harmachis, Hyrgonaphor, Herwennefer, or Horwennefer.

Name: Hui
Comment: She was the mother of Merytre-Hatshepsut, the Great Royal Wife of Pharaoh Thutmose III.

Name: Hunefer
Comment: Hunefer was "Scribe of Divine Offerings", "Overseer of Royal Cattle", and steward of Pharaoh Seti I. Known for his copy of the Egyptian funerary Book of the Dead.

Name: Huni
Comment: The last pharaoh of Egypt of the 3rd dynasty. He was the successor to Khaba.

Name: Huy
Comment: High Priest of Ptah during the reign of the 19th dynasty pharaoh Ramesses II. Huy was succeeded by Pahemnetjer.

Name: Huya
Comment: He was the Superintendent of the Royal Harem, Superintendent of the Treasury and Superintendent of the House, all titles that are associated with Queen Tiye, mother of Akhenaten.

Name: Iaret
Comment: The daughter of Pharaoh Amenhotep II and wife of Thutmose IV.

Name: Ibi
Comment: Chief Steward to the Adorer of the God, Nitocris I, during the reign of Pharaoh Psamtik I. His name is sometimes written as Aba or Abe.

Name: Ibiau
Comment: Ibiau, Ibiaw or Wahibre Ibiau was an Egyptian king of the 13th Dynasty.

Name: Ibiaw
Comment: A vizier under pharaohs Wahibre Ibiau and Merneferre Ay.

Name: Imhotep
Comment: He served under King Djoser as chancellor to the pharaoh and High Priest of Re at Heliopolis. He was revered by later Egyptian dynasties as an architect, engineer, physician, poet and philosopher.

Name: Imyremeshaw
Comment: Imyremeshaw Smenkhkare was an Egyptian king of the 13th dynasty.

Name: Inaros
Comment: An Egyptian rebel ruler who was the son of a Libyan prince named Psamtik. In 460 BC, he revolted against the Persians with the help of his Athenian allies and defeated the Persian army. He was defeated in 454 BC by a Persian army led by Megabyzus. Inaros was captured and executed in 454 BC. Also known as Ienheru, or Inarus.

Name: Inenek-Inti
Comment: A wife of Pharaoh Pepi I Meryre of the 6th dynasty.

Name: Ineni
Comment: Her husband was probably king Merneferre Ay.

Name: Ineni
Date: fl. late-16th and early 15th century BC
Comment: An Egyptian architect and government official of the 18th dynasty, responsible for major construction projects under the pharaohs Amenhotep I, Thutmose I, Thutmose II, Hatshepsut and Thutmose III. Ineni expanded the Temple of Karnak and probably oversaw the construction of Amenhotep I's tomb and mortuary temple.

Name: Inetkawes
Comment: She was the only known child of Pharaoh Djoser and Queen Hetephernebti.

Name: Ini Menkheperre
Comment: Probably pharaoh Rudamun's successor at Thebes but was not a member of his predecessor's 23rd dynasty. Unlike the 23rd dynasty rulers, he was a local king who ruled only at Thebes. Also known as Iny Si-Ese Meryamun.

Name: Inkaef
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Intef the Elder
Comment: Nomarch of Thebes during the first intermediate period, later considered a founding figure of the 11th dynasty.

Name: Intef I
Comment: Intef I Sehertawy was local Egyptian ruler at Thebes, Egypt. He was the first of his dynasty to assume the title of Pharaoh. His authority was contested by the other nomarchs of Egypt, but he had gained control over Koptos, Dendera and the three nomes of Hierakonpolis by the end of his reign.

Name: Intef II
Comment: Intef II Wahankh's capital was located at Thebes, Egypt. After the death of the nomarch Ankhtifi, Intef II was able to unite all the southern nomes down to the First Cataract. By the time Intef II died, he left behind a strong government in Thebes which controlled the whole of Upper Egypt.

Name: Intef III
Comment: Intef III Nakhtnebtepnefer was a king during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Intef V
Comment: Intef V Sehetepkare was an Egyptian king. His name is also written as Antef V or Inyotef V.

Name: Intef VI
Comment: Intef VI Sekhemrewepmaat ruled from Thebes. He lived during the Second Intermediate Period, when Egypt was ruled by multiple kings. His name is also written as Antef VI.

Name: Intef VII
Comment: Intef VII Nubkheperre ruled from Thebes during the Second Intermediate Period, when Egypt was divided by rival dynasties including the Hyksos in Lower Egypt. He was the brother of Intef VI and perhaps the son of Sekhemre Shedtawy Sobekemsaf I. His name is also written as Antef VII.

Name: Intef VIII
Comment: Intef VIII Sekhemreheruhirmaat ruled during the Second Intermediate Period, when Egypt was divided between the Theban-based 17th dynasty in Upper Egypt and the Hyksos 15th dynasty who controlled Lower and part of Middle Egypt. His name is also written as Antef VIII.

Name: Intef
Comment: Served under king Mentuhotep II.

Name: Intefiqer
Comment: An Egyptian noble who was overseer of the city and vizier under the Pharaohs Amenemhet I and Senusret I.

Name: Ipu
Comment: She was the mother of Queen Satiah, Great Royal Wife of Pharaoh Thutmose IV.

Name: Iput
Comment: A daughter of Unas, the last king of 5th dynasty of Egypt. She married Teti, the first pharaoh of the 6th dynasty of Egypt. Their son was Pepi I Meryre and she acted for him as a regent after her husband's death.

Name: Iput II
Comment: Wife of king Pepi II Neferkare.

Name: Iry-Hor
Comment: Predynastic ruler of Egypt, earliest king of Egypt known by name. Ruled Upper Egypt at least as far north as Memphis.

Name: Isesi-ankh
Comment: High official, Overseer of all the works of the King, Overseer of the expedition, Royal companion. Possibly A son of king Djedkare Isesi.

Name: Isesu
Comment: A daughter of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Iset
Comment: She was a secondary wife or concubine of Thutmose II. Iset was the mother of Thutmose III, the only son of Thutmose II.

Name: Iset
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Thutmose III and his Great Royal Wife Merytre-Hatshepsut.

Name: Iset
Comment: Daughter of Amenhotep III and Tiye. She was a sister of Akhenaten. She later married her father.

Name: Iset
Comment: Daughter of Pharaoh Ramesses VI and Nubkhesbed, and a sister of Pharaoh Ramesses VII. Also known as Aset, or Isis.

Name: Iset Ta-Hemdjert
Comment: She was the wife of Ramesses III and the mother of both Ramesses IV and Ramesses VI.

Name: Isetemkheb
Comment: The sister-wife of the Theban High Priest of Amun, Pinudjem II. Isetemkheb was a daughter of the Theban High Priest of Amun and general, Prince Menkheperre, and his wife, Isetemkheb.

Name: Isetnofret
Comment: One of the wives of Pharaoh Ramesses II and was the mother of his heir, Merneptah. Alternatively called: Isis-nofret or Isitnofret.

Name: Isetnofret II
Comment: One of the wives of Pharaoh Merneptah. Alternatively called: Isis-nofret or Isitnofret.

Name: Isidorus
Comment: A native ancient Egyptian priest. He led the native Egyptian revolt against Roman rule during the reign of emperor Marcus Aurelius.

Name: Isu
Comment: He was a son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Itet
Comment: A noblewoman, a wife of Prince Nefermaat, and daughter-in-law of pharaoh Sneferu. Her name is also written as Atet.

Name: Itisen
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu, and of Itet.

Name: Itu
Comment: He was a son of Prince Rahotep and Nofret and grandson of pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Iufaa
Comment: An Egyptian priest and administer of palaces. His undisturbed tomb was found in 1994.

Name: Iufni
Comment: The only record of this Pharaoh comes from the Turin King List.

Name: Iunmin I
Comment: He was possibly a son of king Khafre and served as vizier during the reign of his brother, Menkaure. His name is also written as Yunmin, Iuenmin, and Minuen.

Name: Iunre
Comment: He was a son of king Khafre. His name is also written as Yunre.

Name: Iuput
Comment: Served during the reigns of his father Pharaoh Shoshenq I and his brother Osorkon I. He was also general, army commander and governor of Upper Egypt.

Name: Iuput I
Comment: A pharaoh of Upper Egypt and a co-regent with his father, Pedubast I.

Name: Iuput II
Comment: The ruler of Leontopolis in the Egyptian Delta region. He was an ally of Tefnakht of Sais who resisted the invasion of Lower Egypt by the 25th dynasty Kushite king Piye. After Piye defeated Tefnakht's coalition and conquered Lower Egypt, Iuput II remained in power as the local governor of Leontopolis. Also known as Yuput II.

Name: Iuty
Comment: Tomb in Bubastis

Name: Iuwelot
Comment: A High Priest of Amun at Thebes under the pharaohs Osorkon I and Takelot I.

Name: Iyibkhentre
Comment: An Egyptian or Nubian pretender to the throne, he was an opponent of Amenemhat I but was defeated by him.

Name: Iymeru
Comment: A vizier under pharaohs Khendjer and Imyremeshaw.

Name: Iynefer
Comment: A son of pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Kaaper
Comment: Also called Sheikh el-Beled, he was a priest and scribe known for his wooden statue from Saqqara

Name: Ka (pharaoh)
Comment: Ka, also Sekhem Ka or Ka-Sekhen, was a Predynastic pharaoh of Upper Egypt.

Name: Kaemqed
Comment: A son of princess Nefertnesu and grandson of Pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Kaemsekhem
Comment: A son of prince Kawab and Hetepheres II and grandson of the pharaoh Khufu. He served as the director of the palace.

Name: Kagemni I
Comment: He was a vizier to both Pharaoh Huni and Pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Kagemni
Comment: Vizier during the reign of king Teti. Kagemni's wife Nebtynubkhet Sesheshet was probably the daughter of Teti.

Name: Kakhent
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Kamose
Comment: The last king of the Theban 17th dynasty (reigned c.1555 BC – c.1550 BC). He was probably the son of Seqenenre Tao and Ahhotep I and brother of Ahmose I, founder of the Eighteenth Dynasty.

Name: Kanefer
Comment: The son of pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Kapes
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Takelot I and the mother of Pharaoh Osorkon II.

Name: Karomama
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Sheshonk I and the mother of Pharaoh Osorkon I. Her name is sometimes given as Karamat

Name: Karomama I
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Osorkon II. Karomama was probably a daughter of Pharaoh Takelot I.

Name: Karomama II
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Takelot II. Karomama was a daughter of the High Priest of Amun Nimlot and his wife Tentsepeh. Karomama was the mother of pharaoh Osorkon III.

Name: Karomama Meritmut
Comment: A God's Wife of Amun during the 22nd dynasty. Possibly a daughter of Pharaoh Osorkon II.

Name: Kashta
Comment: A king of the Kushite Dynasty (reigned c. 760 BC – c. 752 BC). Kashta ruled Nubia and he also exercised a strong degree of control over Upper Egypt. During his reign, the native Kushite population adopted Egyptian traditions, religion and culture.

Name: Kawab
Comment: He was the eldest son of Pharaoh Khufu and Queen Meritites I and half-brother of pharaohs Djedefre and Khafre.

Name: Kekheretnebti
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Djedkare Isesi.

Name: Keminub
Comment: An Egyptian noblewoman with the title king's wife who was buried next to the pyramid of the 12th dynasty pharaoh Amenemhet II at Dahshur. For that reason it has been suggested she was his wife. May date to a later period however.

Name: Khaba
Comment: Pharaoh of the 3rd dynasty, possibly succeeded Sanakht, may be the owner of the Layer Pyramid.

Name: Khabash
Comment: A noble based at Sais in Lower Egypt. During the second Persian occupation of Egypt (343–332 BC) he led a revolt against the Persian rule with his eldest son. During the 330s BC, Khabash led an invasion into the kingdom of Kush but was defeated by king Nastasen. Also known as Khababash.

Name: Khabaw
Date: fl. c. early- to mid-18th century BC
Comment: Pharaoh of the 13th dynasty, successor and possible son of Hor Awibre.

Name: Khabekhnet
Comment: He served during the reigns of the pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Khaemtir
Comment: He served during the reigns of the pharaohs Amenmesse and Seti II.

Name: Khaemweset
Comment: He was probably the son of Pharaoh Amenhotep II.

Name: Khaemweset
Comment: A son of Ramesses II and queen Isetnofret. He was a Sem-Priest and later High Priest of Ptah and governor of Memphis. Khaemwaset restored the monuments of earlier kings, such as Shepseskaf, Sahure and Nyuserre Ini, and restored the pyramid of Unas at Saqqara.

Name: Khaemweset
Comment: A son of Pharaoh Ramesses III. He was a priest of Ptah in Memphis.

Name: Khaemwaset
Comment: Vizier under king Ramesses IX, ordered and led investigation about some royal tomb robberies.

Name: Khafre
Comment: He reigned c.2558 BC – c.2532 BC. He was a brother of Djedefre. Khafre had his capital at Memphis and built the second largest pyramid at Giza and is thought to have built the Great Sphinx.

Name: Khamerernebty
Comment: A daughter of the 5th dynasty King Nyuserre Ini and was married to the King's vizier, Ptahshepses.

Name: Khamerernebty I
Comment: She was probably a wife of the pharaoh Khafre and the mother of Menkaura and Khamerernebty II.

Name: Khamerernebty II
Comment: She was probably the daughter of Pharaoh Khafre and Queen Khamerernebty I and was married to her brother Menkaura.

Name: Khamudi
Comment: The last pharaoh of the Hyksos 15th dynasty of Egypt (reigned c.1555 BC – c.1544 BC), who ruled in the northern portion of Egypt. He was defeated by the founding pharaoh of the 18th dynasty, Ahmose I.

Name: Khasekhemwy
Comment: Thought to be the last king of the 2nd dynasty of Egypt. He led several significant military campaigns and built several monuments, still extant, mentioning war against the Northerners.

Name: Khawy
Main Title: Guardian in the Place of Truth
Comment: A guardian in the Place of Truth and servitor of Amun of Opet (Luxor) during the reign of Egyptian pharaoh, Ramesses II.

Name: Khay
Comment: A vizier in the latter part of pharaoh Ramesses II. Khay was the son of Hai and Nub-em-niut.

Name: Khayu
Comment: Predynastic ancient Egyptian king who ruled in the Nile Delta.

Name: Khedebneithirbinet I
Comment: She was probably the wife of the 26th dynasty pharaoh Necho II. She was the mother of his successor, Psamtik II.

Name: Khendjer Userkare
Comment: Khendjer was the earliest known Semitic king of an Egyptian dynasty.

Name: Khenemetneferhedjet I Weret
Comment: A wife of King Senusret II and the mother of Senusret III.

Name: Khenemetneferhedjet II Weret
Comment: A wife of King Senusret III.

Name: Khenemetneferhedjet III
Comment: She was the wife of King Amenemhet III.

Name: Khensa
Comment: Khensa was the sister-wife of the Pharaoh Piye. Her name is sometimes written as Khenensaiuw.

Name: Khentetka
Comment: Khentetka was the wife of the pharaoh Djedefra.

Name: Khenthap
Comment: Kenthap was the mother of Djer and was probably the wife of King Hor-Aha.

Name: Khentimeresh
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu, and Itet.

Name: Khentkaus I
Comment: She was a daughter of Menkaure, possibly a wife of Shepseskaf and mother of Userkaf.

Name: Khentkaus II
Comment: She was a wife of Egyptian Pharaoh Neferirkare Kakai. She was the mother of Neferefre and Nyuserre Ini.

Name: Khentkaus III
Comment: She was a wife of Egyptian Pharaoh Neferefre. She was the mother of Menkauhor.

Name: Khenut
Comment: A wife of King Unas.

Name: Khety I
Comment: Nomarch of Asyut, loyal to the pharaohs of Herakleopolis.

Name: Khety II
Comment: Nomarch of Asyut under king Merykare, grandson of the namesake above.

Name: Kheti
Comment: Treasurer under king Mentuhotep II.

Name: Kheti
Comment: Vizier under king Amenemhet III.

Name: Khnumhotep
Comment: Overseer of the Manicurists in the Palace of King Niuserre. Shares a tomb with Niankhkhnum.

Name: Khnumhotep I
Comment: Nomarch of Men'at Khufu under pharaoh Amenemhat I.

Name: Khnumhotep II
Comment: Nomarch of Men'at Khufu under Amenemhat II and Senusret II, known for his remarkable tomb at Beni Hasan.

Name: Khnumhotep III
Comment: He was the son of the local governor Khnumhotep II, and was promoted high steward and then vizier under Senusret II.

Name: Khufu
Comment: The second pharaoh of the 4th Dynasty (reigned c.2589 BC – c.2566 BC). He is generally accepted as being the builder of the Great Pyramid of Giza. Greek name: Cheops.

Name: Khufukhaf
Comment: Khufukhaf was a son of Pharaoh Khufu and brother of pharaohs Djedefre and Khafre. His mother might have been Queen Henutsen. His wife was Nefertkau II and she was buried with him in Giza.

Name: Khui
Comment: A local pharaoh mainly known for his purported tomb, the so-called Pyramid of Khui in Middle Egypt.

Name: Khuiqer
Comment: An extremely poorly known pharaoh, tentatively attributed to various dynasties from the First to the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Khuit I
Comment: Khuit I was possibly the wife of Pharaoh Menkauhor Kaiu.

Name: Khuit
Comment: Wife of King Teti.

Name: Khyan
Comment: A king of the Hyksos 15th dynasty of Egypt. Also known as Seuserenre Khyan, Khian' or Khayan.

Name: Kiya
Comment: One of the wives of Pharaoh Akhenaten.

Name: Ladice
Comment: The daughter of the Greek Cyrenaean King Battus III and his wife Queen Pheretima. Ladice married Amasis II.

Name: Lagus
Comment: Married to Arsinoe, daughter of Meleager, and reputed father of Ptolemy I Soter.

Name: Lysandra
Comment: The daughter of Ptolemy I Soter and Eurydice, the daughter of Antipater.

Name: Lysimachus
Comment: A son of king Ptolemy II Philadelphus and queen Arsinoe I. He survived both his brother Ptolemy III Euergetes and his nephew, Ptolemy IV Philopator, but was put to death by Sosibius, the minister and guardian of Ptolemy V Epiphanes.

Name: Maathorneferure
Comment: The daughter of the Hittite king Hattusili III and his wife Queen Pudukhepa. She was a sister of Hittite king Tudhaliya IV. Maathorneferure married the Egyptian 19th dynasty Pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Maatkare Mutemhat
Date: fl. c. mid to late-11th century BC
Comment: She was the daughter of High Priest of Amun, Pinedjem I, who was the de facto ruler of Southern Egypt from 1070 BC onwards.

Name: Maatkare
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Osorkon I and the mother of pharaoh Sheshonk II. Maatkare was a daughter of Psusennes II.

Name: Magas of Cyrene
Comment: Following the death of Ptolemy I, Magas tried to gain independence for Cyrene, until he crowned himself king around 276 BC. Magas and Antiochus agreed on a joint attack on Egypt but the armies of Ptolemy II defeated them. Magas managed to maintain Cyrene's independence until his death.

Name: Mahu (noble)
Comment: Mahu was Chief of Police at Akhetaten.

Name: Maia
Comment: The wet-nurse of the Egyptian 18th dynasty king Tutankhamun.

Name: Maiherpri
Comment: An Egyptian noble of Nubian origin. He probably lived during the rule of the 18th dynasty king Thutmose IV. He probably grew up in the royal nursery as a prince of a vassal territory and as an adult was an advisor or bodyguard to the pharaoh.

Name: Malewiebamani
Comment: A Kushite King of Meroe (reigned c.463 BC – c.435 BC). Malewiebamani's mother was probably Queen Saka'aye. Malewiebamani was the son of either Nasakhma (whom he succeeded) or Siaspiqa.

Name: Manetho
Comment: An Egyptian historian and priest from Sebennytos who lived during the Ptolemaic era. He was probably a priest of the sun god Ra at Heliopolis. Manetho wrote the Aegyptiaca (History of Egypt) which is of great interest to Egyptologists and used as evidence for the chronology of the reigns of pharaohs.

Name: Masaharta
Comment: He succeeded his father, Pinedjem I, who had been also been the de facto ruler of Upper Egypt from 1070 BC. Masaharta's mother was Duathathor-Henuttawy, the daughter of Ramesses XI.

Name: Maya
Comment: High Priest of Amun during the reign of king Akhenaten.

Name: Maya
Comment: Overseer of the Treasury during the reign of the pharaohs Tutankhamun, Ay and Horemheb. Maya collected taxes and performed other services such as supervising the preparation of their tombs.

Name: Mehytenweskhet
Comment: Daughter of the High Priest of Re Harsiese, and the Great Royal Wife of pharaoh Psamtik I. Mehytenweskhet was the mother of Necho II, the Divine Adoratrice of Amun Nitocris I and a daughter, Meryetneith.

Name: Meketaten
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Akhenaten and his wife Nefertiti.

Name: Meketre
Comment: Chancellor (treasurer) and chief steward during the reign of the 11th dynasty Egyptian kings Mentuhotep II and Mentuhotep III.

Name: Menes
Comment: Legendary pharaoh of the early dynastic period, credited by classical tradition with having united Upper and Lower Egypt, and being the founder of the 1st dynasty of Egypt. Mainstream consensus identifies him with Narmer.

Name: Menhet
Comment: A minor foreign-born wife of pharaoh Thutmose III who was buried in a lavishly furnished rock-cut tomb in Wady Gabbanat el-Qurud.

Name: Menkare
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Menkauhor Kaiu
Comment: Menkauhor may have been a son of king Niuserre. Queen Meresankh IV and Queen Khuit I may have been consorts for Menkauhor. Menkauhor's successor, Djedkare Isesi, may have been his son.

Name: Menkaure
Comment: He reigned c. 2532 BC – c. 2503 BC, and ordered the construction of the third and smallest of the Pyramids of Giza. His chief queen was Khamerernebty II. He was the successor of Khafre.

Name: Menkheperraseneb I
Comment: High Priest of Amun during the reign of pharaoh Thutmose III. He was possibly the uncle of Menkheperreseneb II.

Name: Menkheperreseneb II
Comment: High Priest of Amun, Superintendent of the Gold and Silver Treasuries and Chief of the Overseers of Craftsmen. He served during the reign of pharaoh Thutmose III.

Name: Menkheperre
Comment: One of two known sons of Pharaoh Thutmose III and his wife Merytre-Hatshepsut.

Name: Menkheperre
Comment: A son of pharaoh Pinedjem I and queen Henuttawy. He was the High Priest of Amun at Thebes and de facto ruler of southern Egypt. Menkheperre married his niece Isetemkheb, daughter of his brother Psusennes I and wife Wiay.

Name: Menna
Comment: An Egyptian artisan and "Scribe of the Fields of the Lord of the Two Lands" probably during the reign of the 18th dynasty king Thutmose IV.

Name: Mentuherkhopshef
Comment: One of the sons of Ramesses III and Iset Ta-Hemdjert

Name: Mentuherkhepeshef
Comment: An Egyptian prince during the 20th dynasty, a son of Pharaoh Ramesses IX.

Name: Mentuhotep
Comment: An Egyptian official and treasurer under the 12th dynasty pharaoh Senusret I.

Name: Mentuhotep
Comment: She was possibly the queen consort of the pharaoh Djehuti Sekhemresementawy.

Name: Mentuhotep I
Comment: A local Egyptian prince at Thebes who became the first acknowledged ruler of the 11th dynasty by assuming the title of first supreme chief of Upper Egypt and, later, declaring himself king over all Egypt.

Name: Mentuhotep II Nebhepetre
Comment: The son of Intef III and Iah. His wife was Tem. His only known son was Mentuhotep III. He was able to effectively reunite ancient Egypt for the first time since the 6th dynasty.

Name: Mentuhotep III Sankhkare
Comment: He continued the building program of his father Mentuhotep II.

Name: Mentuhotep IV Nebtawyre
Comment: The last king of the Egyptian 11th Dynasty (reigned c. 1997 BC – c. 1991 BC).

Name: Mentuhotep V Sewedjara
Comment: A pharaoh of Egypt in the 13th dynasty.

Name: Mentuhotep VI Sankhenre
Comment: A pharaoh of Egypt of the 16th Theban dynasty based in Upper Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period. His predecessor was Sekhemre Sankhtawy Neferhotep III. Mentuhotep VI was succeeded by Nebiriau I.

Name: Mentuhotepi
Comment: Pharaoh during the fragmented second intermediate period ruling over little more than Thebes itself.

Name: Menwi
Comment: A minor foreign-born wife of the 18th dynasty Egyptian pharaoh Thutmose III who was buried in a lavishly furnished rock-cut tomb in Wady Gabbanat el-Qurud.

Name: Merdjefare
Comment: One of the few attested pharaohs of the 14th dynasty, reigning from Avaris over the eastern Nile Delta.

Name: Merefnebef
Comment: He first served at the court of the pharaoh Teti, possibly became vizier during the reign of Userkare, and was dismissed during the reign of Pepi I. (or Unisankh and Fefi)

Name: Merenhor
Comment: He may have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Merenre Nemtyemsaf I
Comment: Merenre was a son of Pepi I and Ankhesenpepi I.

Name: Merenre Nemtyemsaf II
Comment: Briefly king during the 6th dynasty of Egypt (reigned c. 2184 BC – c. 2183 BC), succeeding his long-lived father Pepi II Neferkare.

Name: Mereret
Comment: She was a daughter of Rahotep and Nofret and niece of pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Mereruka
Comment: He was the vizier to the pharaoh Teti and married Teti's daughter, Hert-watet-khet.

Name: Meresamun
Comment: An ancient Egyptian singer-priestess in the inner sanctum at the temple in Karnak.

Name: Meresankh I
Comment: Possibly a lesser wife of pharaoh Huni. Meresankh was the mother of the 4th dynasty pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Meresankh II
Comment: Meresankh II was a daughter of Khufu and Queen Meritites I. She was probably married her half-brother Djedefre, but it is also possible she married the pharaoh Khafre.

Name: Meresankh III
Comment: She was the daughter of Hetepheres II and Prince Kawab. She married king Khafre.

Name: Meresankh IV
Comment: She could have been queen to king Menkauhor Kaiu or Djedkare Isesi.

Name: Meret-Isesi
Comment: Her father was Pharaoh Djedkare.

Name: Meretseger
Comment: She was probably the wife of Senusret III. She was the first Egyptian queen consort to bear the title Great Royal Wife, which became the standard title for chief wives of pharaohs.

Name: Merhotepre Ini
Comment: The son and successor of Merneferre Ay and a king of the late 13th dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Merikare
Comment: A pharaoh during the 10th dynasty of Egypt who controlled territories based around Herakleopolis.

Name: Meritamen
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Thutmose III and Merytre-Hatshepsut.

Name: Meritamen
Comment: A daughter and later Great Royal Wife of the 19th dynasty pharaoh Ramesses II. Her name is also written as Meritamun, Merytamen, Merytamun, and Meryt-Amen.

Name: Meritaten
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Smenkhkare. Meritaten was a daughter of pharaoh Akhenaten and queen Nefertiti. Meritaten also may have ruled as pharaoh in her own right under the name, Ankhkheperure Neferneferuaten.

Name: Meritaten Tasherit
Comment: She was probably the daughter of Meritaten, the eldest daughter of Pharaoh Akhenaten.

Name: Meritites I
Comment: Meritites was a daughter of Sneferu. Meritites married her elder half-brother the pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Meritites II
Comment: Daughter of pharaoh Khufu and his younger half-sister Meritites I. She married Akhethotep, who was a Director of the Palace.

Name: Meritites IV
Comment: She was a wife of king Pepi I.

Name: Merit-Ptah
Comment: A female physician who lived during the 2nd dynasty in Egypt.

Name: Merkare
Comment: Poorly known pharaoh of the late 13th dynasty during the second intermediate period.

Name: Merkheperre
Comment: Poorly known pharaoh of the late 13th dynasty during the second intermediate period.

Name: Merneferre Ay
Comment: Longest reigning king of the 13th Dynasty.

Name: Merneith
Comment: A queen consort and a regent of Egypt during the 1st dynasty. She may have been a ruler of Egypt in her own right. She was king Djet's senior royal wife and the mother of Den.

Name: Merneptah
Date: fl. c. mid to late-13th century BC
Comment: He was a son of Ramesses II. Merneptah had to carry out several military campaigns during his reign,including against the Libyans, who he defeated with the assistance of the Sea Peoples.

Name: Merenptah
Comment: An Egyptian prince during the 19th dynasty, who was probably the son of the pharaoh Merenptah.

Name: Merti
Comment: A minor foreign-born wife of the 18th dynasty Egyptian pharaoh Thutmose III who was buried in a lavishly furnished rock-cut tomb in Wady Gabbanat el-Qurud.

Name: Meru
Comment: An Egyptian official under king Mentuhotep II during the 11th dynasty. Meru was overseer of sealers at the royal court and therefore one of the highest state officials.

Name: Meryatum
Comment: An Egyptian prince and High Priest of Re, the son of the 19th dynasty pharaoh Ramesses II and Nefertari.

Name: Meryatum II
Comment: An Egyptian prince and High Priest of Re. He was a son of the 20th dynasty pharaoh Ramesses III.

Name: Meryhathor
Comment: Possibly the founder of the Herakleopolite 10th dynasty.

Name: Meryibre Khety
Comment: Likely the founder of the Herakleopolite 9th dynasty, thus the Greek Achthoes. Also known as Meryibtawy.

Name: Merymose
Comment: Viceroy of Kush under Amenhotep III. He served for almost the entire four decades of that reign.

Name: Meryptah
Comment: A High Priest of Amun during the reign of the 18th dynasty pharaoh Amenhotep III.

Name: Meryre
Comment: He was also Hereditary Noble and High Official and Fan-bearer on the Right Side of the King which emphasised his close relationship to the 18th dynasty king Akhenaten.

Name: Meryre II
Comment: Superintendent to the 18th dynasty Egyptian queen Nefertiti and was also Royal Scribe, Steward and Overseer of the Two Treasuries and of the Royal Harem of Nefertiti.

Name: Merysekhmet
Comment: He served during the reign of the 19th dynasty pharaoh Merenptah.

Name: Meryteti
Comment: Served as vizier to Pepi I. He was the son of the vizier Mereruka. His mother was princess Sesheshet Watetkhetor.

Name: Merytre-Hatshepsut
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Thutmose III and the mother of Amenhotep II. She was the daughter of a priestess Hui.

Name: Mesehti
Comment: Known for his tomb in Asyut and particularly for the several soldier models within.

Name: Mesen-ka
Comment: Son of a king of the late 2nd Dynasty or early 3rd Dynasty.

Name: Mindjedef
Comment: He was probably a son of Prince Kawab and Hetepheres II. He was a grandson of Pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Minkhaf I
Comment: He was a son of Pharaoh Khufu. His mother may have been Queen Henutsen. He served as vizier during his father's reign.

Name: Minkhaf II
Comment: Great-nephew of Minkhaf I and great-grandson of Khufu.

Name: Minmontu
Comment: The High Priest of Amun during the reign of Ahmose I, an 18th dynasty king of Egypt.

Name: Minmose
Comment: The overseer of works for the 18th dynasty pharaohs Thutmose III and Amenhotep II and took part in expeditions to Syria and Nubia.

Name: Minnefer
Main Title: Supervisor of Palace Attendants, Overseer of Messengers
Comment: Known from a statue.

Name: Mutbenret
Comment: An Egyptian noblewoman and possibly the sister of the 18th dynasty Great Royal Wife Nefertiti. (or Benretmut)

Name: Mutemwiya
Comment: A minor wife of the 18th dynasty Egyptian king Thutmose IV and the mother of Amenhotep III.

Name: Muthis
Comment: Maybe an ephemeral pharaoh usurper of the 29th dynasty.

Name: Mutnedjmet
Comment: Also known as Mutnedjemet, Mutnodjmet, and Mutnodjemet. She was the Great Royal Wife of Horemheb, the last king of the 18th dynasty.

Name: Mutnedjmet
Comment: She was the Great Royal Wife of her brother, Psusennes I, and was the mother of Pharaoh Amenemope. She was the daughter of the High Priest of Amun, Pinedjem I.

Name: Mutnofret
Comment: A queen of Thutmose I, and the mother of Thutmose II. She was probably a daughter of Ahmose I and a sister of Amenhotep I.

Name: Nakht
Comment: Served during the reign of Tuthmose IV. Buried in TT52

Name: Nakhthoreb
Comment: See Nectanebo II

Name: Nakhtmin
Comment: A general during the reign of Pharaoh Tutankhamun. Nakhtmin may have been the son and heir of Pharaoh Ay but died before the end of the Ay's reign.

Name: Nakhtnebef
Comment: See Nectanebo I

Name: Nakhtneith
Comment: Wife to king Djer.

Name: Nakhtpaaten
Comment: Vizier of Pharaoh Akhenaten. Nakhtpaaten succeeded the vizier Ramose in office. Known from his tomb in Amarna.

Name: Nakhtubasterau
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Amasis II. Name also written as Nakhtbastetiru.

Name: Naparaye
Comment: Naparaye was the daughter of King Piye and the sister-wife of King Taharqa.

Name: Narmer
Comment: The pharaoh who is thought to be the successor to the proto-dynastic pharaohs Scorpion and/or Ka, and possibly the unifier of Egypt and founder of the 1st dynasty, and therefore the first pharaoh of all Egypt.

Name: Nasakhma
Comment: Kushite King of Meroe. He was the successor to king Siaspiqa. (or Nasakhmaqa)

Name: Nastasen
Comment: King of Kush (reigned c. 335 BC – c. 310 BC). He was probably the son of King Harsiotef and Queen Pelkha and his wife may have been Sekhmakh. Nastasen defeated an invasion of Kush from Upper Egypt led by a local ruler, Khabbash.

Name: Nauny
Comment: Also known as Nany or Entiuny. She was probably a daughter of High Priest, later Pharaoh Pinedjem I.

Name: Nebamun
Date: fl. c. early to mid-13th century BC
Comment: Vizier during the late 18th and early 19th dynasties of Egypt. He held that office from the reign of Horemheb to the reign of Ramesses II.

Name: Nebankh
Comment: Royal acquaintance and high steward during the reigns of Neferhotep I and Sobekhotep IV of the mid 13th Dynasty.

Name: Nebemakhet
Comment: He was the son of pharaoh Khafre and queen Meresankh III. He was Chief Justice and Vizier to the pharaoh Menkaure.

Name: Nebet
Comment: The wife of king Unas.

Name: Nebet
Comment: A female vizier who held the office during the reign of Pepi I. Nebet's two daughters, Ankhesenpepi I and Ankhesenpepi II married Pepi I. She was married to Khui and their son Djau was a vizier.

Name: Nebetah
Comment: Daughter of Amenhotep III and wife Tiye. She was a younger sister of Akhenaten.

Name: Nebetia
Comment: She was the granddaughter of Pharaoh Thutmose IV and the daughter of Prince Siatum.

Name: Nebetiunet
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Thutmose III and his wife Merytre-Hatshepsut.

Name: Nebetnehat
Comment: A Queen of an unidentified Pharaoh. Her name is only known from an alabaster canopic fragment found in the valley of the Queens.

Name: Nebettawy
Comment: The daughter and a Great Royal Wife of pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Nebiriau I Sewadjenre
Comment: Also known as Nebiryerawet I. A pharaoh of the 16th Theban dynasty based in Upper Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Nebiriau II
Comment: Also known as Nebiryerawet II. A pharaoh of the 16th Theban dynasty based in Upper Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Nebit
Comment: Nebit was an Ancient Egyptian official under king Senusret III.

Name: Nebkaure Khety
Comment: A pharaoh of the Herakleopolite 9th dynasty, also mentioned on The Eloquent Peasant.

Name: Nebmaatre
Comment: Obscur pharaoh of the early 17th dynasty during the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Nebmaatre
Comment: High Priest of Re in Heliopolis. He was probably a son of Ramesses IX.

Name: Nebneteru Tenry
Comment: High Priest of Amun under pharaoh Seti I. Nebneteru's wife, Merytre, was Chief of the Harem of Amun.

Name: Nebnuni
Comment: See Nebnun(i) Semenkare.

Name: Nebre
Comment: See Raneb.

Name: Nebsenre
Comment: Obscur king of the 14th Dynasty, attested by a single inscription on a jar and the Turin canon.

Name: Nebtu
Comment: Wife of the 18th dynasty king, Thutmose III.

Name: Nebtyemneferes
Comment: Daughter of Pharaoh Djedkare.

Name: Nebty-tepites
Comment: Nebty-tepites was a daughter of Prince Horbaef and his half-sister Meresankh II. After Horbaef's death, Meresankh married either the pharaoh Djedefra or the pharaoh Khafre.

Name: Nebwawy
Comment: High Priest of Osiris under the pharaohs Hatshepsut, Thutmose III and Amenhotep II.

Name: Nebwenenef
Comment: High Priest of Amun at the beginning of the reign of Ramesses II. Prior to that, Nebwenenef had served as High Priest of Anhur and High Priest of Hathor during the reign of Seti I.

Name: Neby
Comment: See Neferkare Neby.

Name: Necho I
Comment: Also known as Nekau I. Governor of the Egyptian city of Sais. He was the first attested local Saite king of the 26th dynasty of Egypt (reigned c. 672 BC–c. 664 BC). He was killed by an invading Kushite force under Tantamani.

Name: Necho II
Comment: Also known as Nekau II (reigned c. 610 BC–c. 595 BC). Following the collapse of the Assyrian Empire, the Babylonians under Nebuchadrezzar II fought the armies of Pharaoh Necho II. The Egyptians were defeated and eventually expelled from Syria.

Name: Nectanebo I
Comment: Also known as Nekhtnebef. Nectanebo deposed and killed Nefaarud II, starting the last dynasty of Egyptian kings. He spent much of his reign defending his kingdom against Persian reconquest but still erected many monuments and temples.

Name: Nectanebo II
Comment: Also known as Nakhthoreb, the last king of the 30th dynasty and the last native Egyptian ruler in antiquity. He was placed on the throne by the Spartan king Agesilaus II, who helped him overthrow Teos and fight off a rival pretender. Nectanebo II was defeated by the Persian king Artaxerxes III, and went into exile in Nubia. Egypt once again became a satrapy of the Persian Empire.

Name: Nedjeftet
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Pepi I.

Name: Nedjem
Comment: He was a son of Pharaoh Amenhotep II.

Name: Nedjemib
Comment: She was a daughter of Rahotep and Nofret and niece of pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Nedjemibre
Date: fl. c. early- to mid-18th century BC
Comment: Ephemeral ruler of the 13th dynasty during the Second Intermediate Period. Known only from the Turin canon.

Name: Neferefre
Comment: Also known as Raneferef. He reigned c. 2460 BC – c. 2453 BC.

Name: Neferetnebty
Comment: A wife of pharaoh Sahure. Her name is sometimes written as Neferet-ha-Nebti, or Neferetnebti.

Name: Neferhetepes
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Djedefre.

Name: Neferhotep
Comment: A 13th dynasty Egyptian official and scribe.

Name: Neferhotep I
Comment: He was the son of a Theban military family and brother of King Sobekhotep IV.

Name: Neferhotep III Sekhemre Sankhtawy
Comment: A king during the Theban 16th Dynasty.

Name: Neferirkare
Comment: He reigned c. 2161 BC – c. 2160 BC, during the First Intermediate Period.
