Name: Neferirkare Kakai
Comment: He reigned c. 2477 BC – c. 2467 BC. He married Queen Khentkaus II.

Name: Neferkahor
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkamin
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkamin Anu
Comment: May have been an 8th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkara I
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkare II
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkare III
Comment: A king during the 9th dynasty of Egypt controlling territories based around Herakleopolis.

Name: Neferkare Iymeru
Comment: An Egyptian vizier under king Sobekhotep IV.

Name: Neferkare Khendu
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkare Neby
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period. His mother was probably Queen Ankhesenpepi II and his father was probably Pepi II Neferkare.

Name: Neferkare Pepiseneb
Comment: May have been an 8th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkare Tereru
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkare VII
Comment: The third pharaoh of the 9th dynasty.

Name: Neferkare VIII
Comment: The second pharaoh of the 10th dynasty.

Name: Neferkare
Comment: The last local ruler of Tanis who finally submitted himself to Psamtik I of the 26th dynasty.

Name: Neferkau
Comment: He was a son of Rahotep and Nofret and nephew of pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Neferkauhor
Comment: He reigned c. 2163 BC–c. 2161 BC, during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Neferkaure II
Comment: He reigned c. 2167 BC–c. 2163 BC, during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Nefermaat I
Comment: A son of pharaoh Sneferu. He was a vizier and was a half-brother of Khufu. Nefermaat's wife was Itet.

Name: Nefermaat II
Comment: Vizier during the reign of his cousin pharaoh Khafre. Nefermaat was a son of Princess Nefertkau .

Name: Neferneferuaten Ankhkheperure
Comment: A female Egyptian pharaoh (reigned c.1335 BC – c.1333 BC) toward the end of the Amarna era during the 18th Dynasty. She was probably a daughter of pharaoh Akhenaten.

Name: Neferneferuaten Tasherit
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Akhenaten and his Great Royal Wife Nefertiti.

Name: Neferneferure
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Akhenaten and Great Royal Wife Nefertiti.

Name: Neferronpet
Comment: An Egyptian vizier and a High Priest of Ptah during the reign of pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Nefersheshemre
Comment: A vizier during the early to middle part of the reign of the 6th dynasty Egyptian pharaoh Teti.

Name: Nefertari
Comment: The first Great Royal Wife of Pharaoh Thutmose IV.

Name: Nefertari
Comment: Also known as Nefertari Merytmut, one of the Great Royal Wives of pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Neferthenut
Comment: She was probably the wife of pharaoh Senusret III.

Name: Nefertiabet
Comment: She was a daughter of Pharaoh Khufu and sister of Hetepheres II and Khafre.

Name: Nefertiti
Comment: The Great Royal Wife of Pharaoh Akhenaten. Nefertiti is also known for her bust which was attributed to the sculptor Thutmose.

Name: Nefertkau I
Comment: A daughter of pharaoh Sneferu and a half-sister to Khufu.

Name: Nefertkau II
Comment: The wife and sister of Prince Khufukhaf I, son of the 4th dynasty pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Nefertkau III
Comment: She was probably a daughter of Meresankh II and Prince Horbaef. She was married to an official named Iynefer.

Name: Nefertnesu
Comment: She was a daughter of pharaoh Sneferu and she was a half-sister to pharaoh Khufu.

Name: Neferu III
Comment: She was a daughter of Amenemhat I, wife of her brother, Senusret I, and the mother of Amenemhat II.

Name: Neferuptah
Comment: Also known as Ptahneferu, a daughter of the Egyptian king Amenemhat III of the 12th dynasty. Her sister was the Pharaoh Sobekneferu.

Name: Neferure
Comment: The daughter of two pharaohs, Hatshepsut and Thutmose II. She served in high offices in the Egyptian government and the religious administration.

Name: Nefrubity
Comment: She is sometimes called Akhbetneferu. She was the daughter of Pharaoh Thutmose I and Ahmose, the sister of Hatshepsut and the half-sister of Thutmose II.

Name: Nehesy
Comment: A ruler during the 14th dynasty of Egypt of the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Nehi
Comment: Nehy was in office under Thutmose III.

Name: Neith
Comment: One of the queens of the 6th dynasty pharaoh Pepi II. Neith was probably a daughter of the pharaoh Pepi I and queen Ankhesenpepi I, making her half-sister to pharaoh Pepi II. Neith may be the mother of pharaoh Nemtyemsaf II.

Name: Neithhotep
Comment: Queen of Egypt, and likely wife of Narmer.

Name: Neitiqerty Siptah
Comment: He reigned c. 2183 BC – c. 2181 BC, and was an obscure successor to Merenre Nemtyemsaf II towards the end of the 6th dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Nekauba
Comment: He reigned c. 678 BC – c. 672 BC during the 26th Saite dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Nemtyemsaf I
Comment: see Merenre Nemtyemsaf I

Name: Nemtyemsaf II
Comment: see Merenre Nemtyemsaf II

Name: Nepherites I
Comment: Also known as Nefaarud I. He founded the 29th dynasty of Egypt by defeating and then executing Amyrtaeus. Nepherites was a native of Mendes, which he made his capital. He supported Sparta in its war against the Persians by supplying them with grain and ship building material.

Name: Nepherites II
Comment: Also known as Nefaarud II, a pharaoh of Egypt. Following the death of his father Hakor, he was the last pharaoh of the 29th dynasty. He was deposed and killed by Nectanebo I after ruling Egypt for only 4 months.

Name: Nerikare
Comment: Short-lived pharaoh of the 13th dynasty.

Name: Neserkauhor
Comment: He was a son of Djedkare Isesi.

Name: Nesitanebetashru
Comment: A daughter of the Egyptian nobleman and High Priest of Amun, Pinedjem II, and his wife Neskhons.

Name: Nesitanebetashru
Comment: The wife of Sheshonk II and the mother of Pharaoh Harsiese. She was also a Chantress of Amun.

Name: Nesitaudjatakhet
Comment: Nesitaudjatakhet was a wife of Pharaoh Sheshonk II and the mother of Prince Osorkon D.

Name: Neskhons
Comment: She was the daughter of Smendes II and Takhentdjehuti, and wed her paternal uncle, High Priest Pinedjem II.

Name: Neterkheperre Meryptah
Comment: He was High Priest of Ptah during the reigns of the pharaohs Psusennes I, Amenemope, Osochor and Siamun.

Name: Netjeraperef
Comment: A son of the Egyptian pharaoh Sneferu. He was a half-brother of Khufu and nephew to Hetepheres I.

Name: Netjerkare
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Nikare
Comment: May have been a 7th dynasty king of Egypt during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Nikaure
Comment: A prince, chief justice and vizier during the 4th dynasty. Nikaure was a son of Pharaoh Khafre and Queen Persenet. His wife was Nikanebti.

Name: Nimaethap
Comment: Queen, husband unknown

Name: Nimaethap II
Comment: A queen of Egypt at the end of the 2nd dynasty. Wife of Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.

Name: Nimlot
Comment: A Great Chief of the Ma, known for being the father of pharaoh Shoshenq I and brother of pharaoh Osorkon the Elder.

Name: Nimlot
Comment: A prince, son of pharaoh Shoshenq I; he also was a general and a governor at Herakleopolis Magna.

Name: Nimlot
Comment: A High Priest of Amun at Thebes during the latter part of the reign of his father, pharaoh Osorkon II.

Name: Nimlot
Comment: A local pharaoh at Hermopolis during the 25th dynasty, he submitted himself to Piye and is depicted on the latter's Victory stela.

Name: Nitocris
Comment: May have been the last pharaoh of the Egyptian 6th Dynasty. However, her historicity has been questioned.

Name: Nitocris I
Date: fl. c. mid-7th to early-6th century BC
Comment: Also known as Nitiqret, she was the Divine Adoratrice of Amun or God's Wife of Amun for over 70 years. She was the daughter of the Saite pharaoh Psamtik I.

Name: Nitocris II
Comment: Daughter of pharaoh Amasis II and a female High Priest of Amun.

Name: Nodjmet
Comment: A noblewoman, wife of the High Priest of Amun Herihor and/or Piankh.

Name: Nofret
Comment: A noblewoman and princess who lived during the 4th dynasty of Egypt. Nofret married Prince Rahotep, who was a son of Pharaoh Sneferu.

Name: Nofret II
Comment: She was a daughter of Amenemhat II and wife of Senusret II.

Name: Nubhetepti-khered
Comment: An Egyptian king's daughter during the 13th dynasty. Probably a daughter of King Hor.

Name: Nubkhaes
Comment: A 13th dynasty Egyptian queen whose husband is assumed to be one of the successors of pharaoh Sobekhotep IV.

Name: Nubkhesbed
Comment: She was the Great Royal Wife of Pharaoh Ramesses VI and mother of Pharaoh Ramesses VII.

Name: Nubwenet
Comment: Also known as Nebuunet, an Egyptian queen consort and a wife of the 6th dynasty pharaoh Pepi I.

Name: Nuya
Comment: Poorly known pharaoh of the 14th dynasty, likely of Semitic descent and reigning over the eastern Nile Delta.

Name: Nykara
Comment: Known from a granite statue of Nykara and his family, now at the Brooklyn Museum.

Name: Nynetjer
Comment: A long-lived king of the mid 2nd dynasty of Egypt. It is possible that he was a son of his predecessor Raneb.

Name: Nyuserre Ini
Comment: Also known as Neuserre Izi, Niuserre Isi, Nyuserra, and Rathoris. A 5th dynasty pharaoh of Egypt (reigned c. 2453 BC – c. 2422 BC).

Name: Osorkon the Elder
Comment: Osorkon Akheperre Setepenre reigned c. 992 BC – c. 986 BC, and was the first pharaoh of Libyan extraction to rule Egypt. He was the son of Shoshenq, the Great Chief of the Ma.

Name: Osorkon I
Comment: He was the son of Sheshonk I and his chief consort, Karomat. Osorkon I's reign was long and prosperous and is known for many temple building projects.

Name: Osorkon II
Comment: The son of Takelot I and Queen Kapes. He ruled Egypt from Tanis. After succeeding his father, he faced a revolt from his cousin, Harsiese, who controlled Thebes. However, Osorkon II was able to unite Egypt after Harsiese's death. Further names include 'Usermaatre Setepenamun.

Name: Osorkon III
Comment: Usermaatre Setepenamun Si-Ese was a pharaoh of Upper Egypt based in Thebes. He was also a High Priest of Amun. He was a son of Takelot II and Queen Karomama II. During his reign, he defeated the rival forces of Sheshonk IV.

Name: Osorkon IV
Comment: A ruler of Lower Egypt who was based in Tanis and therefore one of the 22nd dynasty pharaoh Shoshenq V's successors.

Name: Osorkon C
Comment: A Great Chief of the Ma and governor of Sais, predecessor of pharaoh Tefnakht of the 24th Dynasty.

Name: Paanchi
Comment: see Piye

Name: Pabasa
Comment: Chief Steward to the Divine Adoratrice of Amun, Nitocris I.

Name: Pageti
Comment: A daughter of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Pahemnetjer
Comment: A High Priest of Ptah during the reign of Ramesses II. Pahemnetjer succeeded Huy as High Priest of Ptah.

Name: Pami Usermaatre Setepenre
Comment: He reigned c. 785 BC – c. 778 BC, and was a member of the Meshwesh Libyans then ruling the country.

Name: Panehesy
Comment: High Priest of the Aten in the temple of Aten in Akhetaten during the reign of Akhenaten.

Name: Panehesy
Main Title: Prophet of Amenhotep (I) of the Forecourt
Comment: He served during the reign of Pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Panehesy
Comment: He served during the reign of Pharaoh Merenptah.

Name: Paraemheb
Comment: A vizier of Egypt during the reigns of the pharaohs Amenmesse and Seti II. Also known as Pre'em'hab.

Name: Pareherwenemef
Comment: He was a son of pharaoh Ramesses II and Queen Nefertari.

Name: Pareherwenemef
Comment: A son of pharaoh Ramesses III.

Name: Parennefer called Wennefer
Date: fl. c. mid to late-14th century BC
Comment: High Priest of Amun during the reigns of the 18th dynasty pharaohs Tutankhamen and Horemheb.

Name: Parennefer
Comment: Pharaoh Akhenaten's close adviser both before and after Akhenaten came to the throne.

Name: Pasenhor
Comment: Priest of Ptah under pharaoh Shoshenq V, known for his long genealogy written on an Apis burial stela.

Name: Paser I
Comment: Paser I likely served during the reigns of Ay and Horemheb

Name: Paser
Date: fl. c. early to mid-13th century BC
Comment: Vizier during the reigns of pharaohs Seti I and Ramesses II. Later he became a High Priest of Amun.

Name: Paser II
Comment: Paser II was the son of the High Priest of Min and Isis named Minmose. He was a King's son of Kush, overseer of the Southern Lands, and king's scribe.

Name: Pashedu
Comment: Lived in Deir el-Medina on the west bank of the Nile, opposite Thebes, during the reign of Seti I.

Name: Patareshnes
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Sheshonk I. Her name is sometimes written as Patoreshnes or Penreshnes.

Name: Paweraa
Comment: Mayor of Western Thebes during a series of tomb robberies that occurred in the Valley of the Kings during the late New Kingdom.

Name: Pawura
Comment: An Egyptian official mentioned in the Amarna letters. He is referred to as an Egyptian "archer–commander" and an "irpi–official".

Name: Pebatjma
Comment: Wife of King Kashta and mother of King Piye (possibly), King Shabaka, God's Wife Amenirdis I, Queens Khensa and Peksater.

Name: Pebekkamen
Comment: One of the key conspirators in the Harem conspiracy, a plot to overthrow Pharaoh Ramesses III. Pebekkamen had served as chief of the chamber to Ramesses. Following his trial, Pebekkamen was executed.

Name: Pediamenopet
Comment: A librarian, archivist and Chief Lector Priest during the Egyptian 25th and 26th dynasties who amassed enough wealth to build a labyrinthine tomb covered with frescoes and hieroglyphics.

Name: Pediese
Comment: Pediese, married to the great-great-granddaughter of Shoshenq III, was one of a number of princes ruling Lower Egypt. He was of Libyan descent, a chief of the Ma. He ruled from Athribis.

Name: Pediese, chief of the Ma
Comment: Involved in the replacement of an Apis bull which had died in the 28th year of the reign of Shoshenq III.

Name: Pehen-Ptah
Comment: Official in charge of the sculptors of the king.

Name: Petiese
Comment: Petiese I, son of Ireturu, administered Upper Egypt. In 651 BCE he had his priestly offices confirmed by Psamtik I.

Name: Pedubast I
Comment: A king of Libyan ancestry (reigned c. 829 BC – c. 804 BC) . He was the main opponent to the 23rd dynasty Upper Egyptian pharaohs Takelot II and Osorkon III during a protracted civil war between these two competing sides.

Name: Pedubast II
Comment: A pharaoh of Lower Egypt (reigned c. 740 BC – c. 730 BC) associated with the 22nd dynasty. He was a possible son and successor to Shoshenq V.

Name: Peftjauawybast
Comment: A local pharaoh at Herakleopolis Magna who submitted himself to the 25th dynasty pharaoh Piye as shown on the latter's Victory stela. Also called Peftjaubast.

Name: Peksater
Comment: She was a daughter of King Kashta and Queen Pebatjma and a wife of the pharaoh, Piye.

Name: Penebui
Comment: Wife of King Djer.

Name: Pennesuttawy
Comment: A general and superintendent of the Southern Lands (Kush) at the beginning of the 19th dynasty of Egypt. Pennesuttawy was a brother of the High Priest of Amun, Parennefer.

Name: Pensekhmet
Comment: He served during the reign of the 19th dynasty pharaoh Merenptah.

Name: Pentawer
Comment: A son of Pharaoh Ramesses III and Queen Tiye. He was to be the beneficiary of a "harem conspiracy" planned by his mother to assassinate the pharaoh. The plot failed and Pentawer was forced to commit suicide.

Name: Penthu
Comment: The seal-bearer of the king, king's scribe, chief of physicians and chamberlain to the 18th dynasty pharaoh Akhenaten.

Name: Pentu
Comment: Vizier of Egypt during the reign of pharaoh Tutankhamun. Also written as Pentju.

Name: Pepi I Meryre
Comment: Pepi I's long reign was marked by an aggressive expansion into Nubia and the spread of trade to far-flung areas such as Lebanon and the Somali coast, but also the growing power of the nomarchs.

Name: Pepi II Neferkare
Comment: He was the son of Merenre and Ankhesenpepi II. His lengthy reign was marked by a sharp decline of the Old Kingdom as the power of the nomarchs grew.

Name: Pepi III Seneferankhre
Comment: Obscur ruler of the second intermediate period, possibly a vassal of the Hyksos kings or a king of the 16th dynasty

Name: Perneb
Comment: He was a son of the 2nd dynasty pharaoh Hotepsekhemwy.

Name: Persenet
Comment: She may have been a daughter of King Khufu and a wife of King Khafre.

Name: Peseshet
Comment: Her title was "lady overseer of the female physicians,"but whether she was a physician herself is uncertain. She had a son, Akhethetep, in whose mastaba at Giza her personal stela was found.

Name: Petubastis III
Comment: An Egyptian ruler who revolted against Persian rule under the satrap Aryandes. He was probably a member of the old royal Saitic line, who attempted to seize power around 522 BC. Aryandes probably quelled the rebellion.(or Seheruibre Padibastet)

Name: Piankh
Comment: High Priest of Amun who led an army against Pinehesy, viceroy of Kush, who had conquered large parts of Upper Egypt and succeeded in driving him back into Nubia.

Name: Pihuri
Comment: An Egyptian commissioner in the "Land of Retenu" (Canaan) mentioned in the Amarna letters. He probably served under pharaohs Amenhotep III and Akhenaten. His name is sometimes written as Pakhura.

Name: Pimay
Comment: Son of king Sheshonk III. He served as a 'Great Chief of the Ma' during his father's reign.

Name: Pinedjem I
Comment: High Priest of Amun at Thebes in Egypt and the de facto ruler of Middle and Upper Egypt from 1054 BC. He asserted his virtual independence from the 21st dynasty based at Tanis. He married Duathathor-Henuttawy, a daughter of Ramesses XI.

Name: Pinedjem II
Comment: High Priest of Amun at Thebes in Egypt and the de facto ruler of the south of the country. He married his sister Isetemkheb and his niece Nesikhons, the daughter of his brother Smendes II.

Name: Pinehesy
Comment: Served during the reign of pharaoh Ramesses XI. Pinehesy extended his influence over much of the south of Egypt defying Ramesses XI. However, the High Priest of Amun, Herihor, was able to drive Pinehesy back into Nubia. Also known as Panehesy or Panehasy.

Name: Pipi
Comment: High Priest of Ptah, a contemporary of Pharaoh Psusennes I. He was the father of the High Priest of Ptah Harsiese.

Name: Piye
Comment: A Kushite king and founder of the 25th dynasty of Egypt who ruled from the city of Napata. As ruler of Nubia and Upper Egypt, Piye took advantage of the squabbling of Egypt's rulers to expand Nubia's power beyond Thebes into Lower Egypt receiving the submission of the kings of the Nile Delta.

Name: Potasimto
Comment: Commander of the Greek troops during an expedition against Nubia under pharaoh Psamtik II; his real Egyptian name was Padismatawy.

Name: Pothinus
Comment: An official under Pharaoh Ptolemy XII. When Ptolemy XII died in 51 BC, as his son Ptolemy XIII was under age, Pothinus was appointed as his regent. Pothinus used his influence to turn Ptolemy XIII against Cleopatra VII. In the resultant civil war, Cleopatra VII and Julius Caesar prevailed and Pothinus was executed in 47 BC.

Name: Prehotep I
Comment: Vizier during the latter part of the reign of pharaoh Ramesses II. Also known as Rahotep, Parahotep, Parehotp.

Name: Prehotep II
Comment: Vizier during the latter part of the reign of pharaoh Ramesses II. Parahotep was the son of the High Priest of Ptah Pahemnetjer. Also known as Rahotep, Parahotep, Parehotp.

Name: Psammetichus IV
Comment: An Egyptian ruler who rebelled to the Persian occupation.

Name: Psammuthes
Comment: Upon the death of Nepherites I, two rival factions fought for the throne: one supported Muthis son of Nefaarud, and the other supported an usurper named Psammuthes. Both men were eventually defeated by a general named Hakor.

Name: Psamtik I Wahibre
Comment: Psamtik managed to unite all of Egypt and free the country from Assyrian and Nubian control within the first ten years of his reign. (or Psammeticus or Psammetichus)

Name: Psamtik II
Comment: In 592 BC, Psamtik II marched deep into Nubia and inflicted a heavy defeat on the kingdom of Kush.(or Psammetichus or Psammeticus)

Name: Psamtik III
Comment: The last pharaoh of the 26th dynasty of Egypt. Psamtik had ruled Egypt for only six months before the Persian invasion led by King Cambyses II. Psamtik was defeated at Pelusium and later executed by the Persians.(or Psammetichus or Psammeticus)

Name: Psusennes I
Comment: He was the son of Pinedjem I and Henuttawy, a daughter of Ramesses XI. He married his sister Mutnedjmet.(or Psibkhanno or Hor-Pasebakhaenniut I)

Name: Psusennes II Titkheperure
Comment: The last king of the 21st dynasty of Egypt. He was a High Priest of Amun at Thebes and the son of Pinedjem II and Istemkheb.(or Tyetkheperre Psusennes II or Hor-Pasebakhaenniut II)

Name: Psusennes III
Comment: A High Priest of Amun at Thebes towards the end of the 21st Dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Ptahhotep
Comment: He was the city administrator and vizier during the reign of Djedkare Isesi. He is credited with authoring "The Instruction of Ptahhotep", which was meant to instruct young men in appropriate behaviour.

Name: Ptahmose
Comment: He served under pharaohs Thutmose IV and Amenhotep III. Ptahmose also held the titles of count and governor, and Sem-priest.

Name: Ptahmose
Comment: Treasurer under the 18th dynasty pharaoh Amenhotep III and known from a statue.

Name: Ptahmose
Comment: High Priest of Amun and vizier of southern Egypt under the 18th dynasty pharaoh Amenhotep III.

Name: Ptahshepses
Comment: The vizier and son-in-law of king Niuserre. His mastaba complex in Abusir is considered by many to be the most extensive and architecturally unique non-royal tomb of the Old Kingdom.

Name: Ptolemy Apion
Comment: The last Greek Cyrenaean King (reigned 116 BC – 96 BC) and was a member of the Ptolemaic dynasty. He was a son of Pharaoh Ptolemy VIII Physcon of Egypt. When Ptolemy VIII died, Ptolemy Apion inherited Cyrenaica and became its king.

Name: Ptolemy Eupator
Comment: The son of Ptolemy VI Philometor and Cleopatra II and, for a short time before his death, reigned as co-ruler with his father.

Name: Ptolemy Keraunos
Comment: King of Macedon (reigned 281 BC – 279 BC). He was the eldest son of Ptolemy I Soter and Eurydice. Keraunos was killed during a battle against the Gauls of Bolgius.

Name: Ptolemy of Mauretania
Comment: The last king of Mauretania (reigned 23 AD-40 AD). Ptolemy was the son of King Juba II and Queen Cleopatra Selene II. With the support of Roman forces, Ptolemy was able to end Berber revolts by 24 AD. In 40 AD, Caligula invited Ptolemy to Rome where he was killed on Caligula's orders.

Name: Ptolemy Philadelphus
Comment: Son of Cleopatra VII and Mark Antony. In 34 BC, at the Donations of Alexandria, Ptolemy was made ruler of Syria, Phoenicia and Cilicia. Octavian took Ptolemy and his siblings to Rome to be paraded in his military triumph.

Name: Ptolemy I Soter I
Comment: A Macedonian general under Alexander the Great, who became ruler of Egypt (reigned 323 BC–283 BC). In 305 BC he took the title of pharaoh. When Alexander died in 323 BC Ptolemy was appointed satrap of Egypt and in the wars that followed was able to securely hold Egypt.

Name: Ptolemy II Philadelphus
Comment: He reigned 283 BC – 246 BC. He was the son of Ptolemy I Soter and Berenice. Ptolemy expanded the library in Alexandria and patronized scientific research. Although an enthusiast for Hellenic culture, he also adopted Egyptian religious concepts. Ptolemy's first marriage was to Arsinoë I, daughter of Lysimachus, and later he married his sister Arsinoë II.

Name: Ptolemy III Euergetes
Comment: He married Berenice of Cyrene. Following Ptolemy's eldest sister Berenice Phernophorus’ murder by the Seleucid rulers in Syria, Ptolemy III invaded Syria. His forces occupied Antioch and even reached Babylon. In exchange for peace in 241 BC, Ptolemy was awarded territories on the northern coast of Syria. Under his rule, the Ptolemaic kingdom reached the height of its power.

Name: Ptolemy IV Philopator
Comment: He was a son of Ptolemy III and Berenice II. During his reign, the decline of the Ptolemaic kingdom began. Ptolemy IV responded effectively to the attacks of Antiochus III on Coele-Syria and Judea and his victory at Raphia (217 BC) secured the northern borders of the kingdom for the remainder of his reign. The native population of Upper Egypt revolted, creating a separate state for twenty years.

Name: Ptolemy V Epiphanes
Comment: A son of Ptolemy IV and Arsinoe III and a king of the Ptolemaic dynasty (reigned 204 BC–181 BC). Ptolemy IV's favourites, Agathocles and Sosibius, became Ptolemy V's regents. In 202 BC, a general, Tlepolemus, revolted and killed the two regents. During his reign lands in Caria, Thrace, Coele-Syria, including Judea, were lost. However, Upper Egypt was brought back under Ptolemaic control.

Name: Ptolemy VI Philometor
Comment: In 170 BC, Antiochus IV invaded Egypt twice retaining Ptolemy VI as a puppet king. In 164 BC, he was driven off the throne by Ptolemy VIII, but was quickly restored by the Alexandrians after which he ruled uneasily, cruelly suppressing frequent rebellions and facing a growing Roman interference. Ptolemy VI was killed in the Battle of Antioch.

Name: Ptolemy VII Neos Philopator
Comment: He was possibly the son of Ptolemy VI and Cleopatra II and reigned briefly with his father in 145 BC, and for a short time after that, but was murdered by his uncle, Ptolemy VIII, who succeeded him.

Name: Ptolemy VIII Euergetes II Physcon
Comment: He reigned 170 BC – 163 BC, 145 BC – 131 BC, and 127 BC – 116 BC. In 170 BC Antiochus IV invaded Egypt and captured Ptolemy VI and let him rule as a puppet monarch. But the Alexandrians chose Ptolemy VIII as king. While Ptolemy VI went to Rome to gain support, Ptolemy VIII's ruled, but was unpopular. So in 163 BC, Ptolemy VI returned to rule Egypt while Ptolemy VIII ruled Cyrenaica. When Ptolemy VI died, Ptolemy VIII took the throne. In 131 BC, the people of Alexandria rioted and Ptolemy VIII escaped to Cyprus until he regained power in 127 BC.

Name: Ptolemy IX Soter II Lathyros
Comment: He reigned 116 BC – 110 BC, 109 BC – 107 BC and 88 BC – 81 BC, with intervening periods ruled by his brother, Ptolemy X Alexander as their mother Cleopatra III played both brothers off against each other.

Name: Ptolemy X Alexander
Comment: He reigned 110 BC – 109 BC and 107 BC – 88 BC with intervening periods ruled by his brother, Ptolemy IX as their mother Cleopatra III played both brothers off against each other.

Name: Ptolemy XI Alexander II
Comment: He ruled Egypt for a few days in 80 BC. Ptolemy XI was a son of Ptolemy X Alexander and either Cleopatra Selene or Berenice III.

Name: Ptolemy XII Neos Dionysos Theos Philopator Theos Philadelphos
Comment: During his reign, Egypt lost Cyprus and Cyrenaica. Ptolemy XII attempted to secure his position through a pro-Roman policy, but the Egyptians rebelled against his high taxes. Ptolemy XII then fled to Rome and his daughter Berenice IV became queen of Egypt. Ptolemy XII was able to recover his throne in 55 BC with the support of Roman soldiers and mercenaries.

Name: Ptolemy XIII Theos Philopator
Comment: He was a son of Ptolemy XII and succeeded his father in 51 BC as co-ruler with his wife and older sister Cleopatra VII. In 48 BC, Ptolemy XIII attempted to depose Cleopatra VII leading civil war in Egypt. Julius Caesar intervened, enabling Cleopatra VII to regain Egyptian throne and forcing Ptolemy XIII to flee the city. Ptolemy XIII drowned while attempting to cross the Nile.

Name: Ptolemy XIV
Comment: He was a son of Ptolemy XII. Following the death of his older brother Ptolemy XIII, Ptolemy XIV ruled with his older sister, Cleopatra VII. Cleopatra also married her new co-ruler but continued as Julius Caesar's lover. When Caesar was murdered in Rome, Cleopatra poisoned Ptolemy XIV and replaced him with Ptolemy XV Caesarion, her son by Caesar.

Name: Ptolemy XV Philopator Philometor Caesar
Comment: see Caesarion

Name: Puimre
Comment: Served during the reigns of Thutmose III and Hatshepsut.

Name: Pyhia
Comment: An Egyptian princess, a daughter of Thutmose IV. Her name is sometimes written as Pyihia or Petepihu.

Name: Qa'a
Comment: The last king of the 1st dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Qakare Ibi
Comment: He reigned c. 2169 BC – c. 2167 BC, during the First Intermediate Period.

Name: Qakare Ini
Comment: An Egyptian or Nubian pretender to the throne, he was an opponent of Amenemhat I but was defeated by him.

Name: Qalhata
Comment: Qalhata was a daughter of King Piye and a queen consort to her brother Shabaka.

Name: Qar
Comment: Physiciant and priest of the mortuary cults of Khafre and Menkaure under Pepi I

Name: Qareh
Comment: Either a pharaoh of Canaanite descent reigning over the eastern Nile Delta in the early 14th Dynasty or a vassal of the Hyksos kings.

Name: Qen
Comment: Qen lived in Deir el-Medina during the reign of Ramesses II. His titles included Servant in the Place of Truth, meaning that he work on the excavation and decoration of nearby royal tombs.

Name: Qenna
Comment: Known from the Papyrus of Qenna, a part of the Book of the Dead.

Name: Raemka
Comment: Possibly a son of Pharaoh Menkauhor Kaiu. Raemka was buried in Saqqara.

Name: Raherka
Comment: Raherka was an official known mainly from the pair statue with his wife: The statue of Raherka and Meresankh

Name: Rahotep
Comment: Also known as Sekhenrewahkhaw Rahotep. He reigned during the Second Intermediate Period, when Egypt was ruled by a number of kings at the same time.

Name: Rahotep
Comment: He was probably a son of pharaoh Sneferu and his first wife, although his father could have been Huni. Statues of Rahotep and his wife Nofret were found in his mastaba in Meidum.

Name: Ramesses I Menpehtyre
Date: fl. c. late-14th to early 13th century BC
Comment: The founding pharaoh of Egypt's 19th dynasty (reigned c. 1292 BC – c. 1290 BC) . Originally called Paramessu, Ramesses I was born into a noble military family from the Nile delta region. Horemheb, the last pharaoh of the 18th dynasty, appointed him as his Vizier, and later, as his heir.

Name: Ramesses II the Great
Comment: He is regarded as Ancient Egypt's greatest and most powerful pharaoh. Ramesses II led successful expeditions north into Canaan, Lebanon and Syria and south into Nubia. He focused on building cities, temples and monuments and established the city of Pi-Ramesses in the Nile Delta as his new capital.

Name: Ramesses III Usimare
Comment: The last great New Kingdom king to wield any substantial authority over Egypt. He was the son of Setnakhte and Queen Tiy-Merenese. During his long reign, Egypt was beset by foreign invaders (including the “Sea Peoples” and the Libyans).

Name: Ramesses IV Heqamaatre
Comment: he reigned c. 1155 BC – c. 1149 BC. A son of Ramesses III, he initiated a substantial building program including an enlargement of the Temple of Khonsu at Karnak. Also known as Amonhirkhopshef.

Name: Ramesses V Usermare Sekhepenre
Comment: The son of Ramesses IV and Queen Duatentopet. During his reign the power of the priesthood of Amun continued to grow, controlling the state's finances and much of the temple land in the country at the expense of the pharaohs.

Name: Ramesses VI
Comment: A son of Ramesses III and Iset Ta-Hemdjert. Egypt's political and economic decline continued during his reign. At Thebes, the power of the chief priests of Amun continued to grow at the expense of the pharaohs.

Name: Ramesses VII Usermaatre Meryamun Setepenre
Comment: A son of Ramesses VI.

Name: Ramesses VIII Usermare Akhenamun
Comment: One of the last surviving sons of Ramesses III. Also known as Ramesses Sethherkhepshef Meryamun.

Name: Ramesses IX
Comment: The son of Montuherkhopshef and grandson of Ramesses III. He reigned c. 1129 BC – c. 1111 BC.

Name: Ramesses X Khepermare
Comment: A pharaoh of the 20th dynasty of Egypt (reigned c. 1111 BC – c. 1107 BC). He was possibly a son of Ramesses IX and husband of Queen Tyti, but this is unproven.

Name: Ramesses XI
Comment: The last king of the 20th dynasty of Egypt. He was probably the son of Ramesses X and Queen Tyti. Ramesses XI's reign saw the continuing disintegration of the Egyptian state. By late in his reign, he was forced to share power with the High Priest of Amun, Herihor, who controlled Thebes and Upper Egypt, and Smendes, who as governor, controlled Lower Egypt.

Name: Ramesses
Comment: The eldest son of Pharaoh Ramesses II and Queen Isetnofret. He was the heir to the Egyptian throne but pre-deceased his father.

Name: Ramesses-Meryamun-Nebweben
Comment: A son of pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Ramessesnakht
Comment: Appointed as the High Priest of Amun at Thebes under pharaoh Ramesses IV. He held this office until the reign of Ramesses IX. It was during Ramessesnakht's tenure that the power and importance of the Amun priesthood grew while the pharaoh's power began to noticeably decline.

Name: Ramose
Comment: Probably the son of Pharaoh Ahmose I.

Name: Ramose
Comment: A noble man, Governor of Thebes and vizier under pharaohs Amenhotep III and Akhenaten.

Name: Raneb
Date: fl. c. late-29th to early-28th century BC
Comment: A king during the 2nd dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Ranefer
Comment: A son of pharaoh Sneferu, the first ruler of the 4th dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Rashepses
Comment: Rashepses served under pharaoh Djedkare Isesi.

Name: Rawer
Comment: Great-grandson of Khufu, brother of Minkhaf II.

Name: Rehuerdjersen
Comment: A treasurer who held this office under pharaoh Amenemhet I.

Name: Rekhetre
Comment: An Egyptian queen from the late 4th dynasty or early 5th dynasty. She was a daughter of Pharaoh Khafre. Rekhetre was possibly the wife of one of Khafre's successors as pharaoh.

Name: Rekhmire
Comment: A noble and official, who served as Governor of Thebes and vizier during the reigns of Tuthmosis III and Amenhotep II. He was also High Priest of Annu or Heliopolis.

Name: Renseneb
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th dynasty. Alternate spelling: Ranisonb.

Name: Reptynub
Comment: She was the wife of King Nyuserre Ini. Her name is also written as Repytnub and Reputnebu.

Name: Reputnebty
Comment: She was a daughter of pharaoh Nyuserre Ini and possibly queen Reptynub.

Name: Roma-Roi
Date: fl. c. mid to late-13th century BC
Comment: High Priest of Amun towards the end of the reign of Ramesses II and into the reigns of Merenptah and possibly Seti II.

Name: Rudamun Usermaatre Setepenamun Meryamun
Comment: The last pharaoh of the 23rd dynasty based in Upper Egypt. He was the younger son of Osorkon III, and the brother of Takelot III.

Name: Sabef
Comment: An Ancient Egyptian official under king Qa'a in the 1st dynasty.

Name: Sabni
Comment: An Ancient Egyptian expedition under king Pepy II buried at Qubbet el-Hawa..

Name: Sabu called Ibebi
Comment: A High Priest of Ptah during the reigns king Unas and king Teti.

Name: Sabu called Thety
Comment: A High Priest of Ptah during the reign of king Teti. He was the successor of Sabu Ibebi and probably his son.

Name: Sahure
Comment: Son of queen Neferhetepes and his father was probably Userkaf. Sahure established a navy and sent the fleet to Punt. He traded with states and cities in the eastern Mediterranean.

Name: Sakir-Har
Comment: A king of the Hyksos 15th dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Salitis
Comment: According to Manetho, the first pharaoh of the Hyksos 15th dynasty of Egypt. The Hyksos founded the city of Avaris which became their capital.

Name: Sanakht
Comment: He reigned c. 2686 BC – c. 2668 BC, and was probably the first pharaoh of the 3rd dynasty of Egypt. Referred to as Sanakhte or Nebka.

Name: Sankhenre Sewadjtu
Comment: A king of Egypt's 13th dynasty at a time when the kings’ control over all of Egypt was receding.

Name: Satiah
Comment: An Egyptian queen, the Great Royal Wife of Thutmose III. Also referred to as Sitiah or Sitioh.

Name: Sebkay
Comment: A pharaoh of the early 13th dynasty, known from a magic wand.

Name: Scota
Dynasty: in Irish mythology, Scottish mythology, and pseudohistory,
Comment: An Egyptian princess,. Also referred to as Scotia .

Name: Sedjefakare Amenemhat
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th dynasty.

Name: Segerseni
Comment: Egyptian or Nubian pretender to the throne, he was an opponent of Amenemhat I but was defeated by him.

Name: Sehebre
Comment: Pharaoh of the 14th dynasty, probably of Canaanite descent and reigning over the eastern Nile Delta during the second intermediate period.

Name: Seheqenre Sankhptahi
Comment: Among the last pharaohs of the 13th dynasty, shortly before its collapse under the Hyksos.

Name: Sehetepre
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th dynasty.

Name: Sekhemib-Perenmaat
Comment: A king during the Egyptian 2nd dynasty, who may have been the same individual as Peribsen, or, more likely, was a separate king who ruled Lower Egypt at the same time that Peribsen ruled Upper Egypt.

Name: Sekhemkare
Comment: A vizier during the reigns of kings Userkaf and Sahure. He was a son of king Khafre and queen Hekenuhedjet.

Name: Sekhemkare
Comment: see Amenemhat V Sekhemkare

Name: Sekhemkhet
Comment: A pharaoh in Egypt during the 3rd dynasty.

Name: Sekhemre Khutawy
Comment: Sekhemre Khutawy Sobekhotep I was an Egyptian king of the 13th Dynasty

Name: Sekheperenre
Comment: Pharaoh of the 14th dynasty, probably of Canaanite descent, reigning over the eastern Delta during the mid second intermediate period.

Name: Sekhmakh
Comment: The wife of the Nubian king Nastasen.

Name: Semat
Comment: Possibly a wife of the 1st dynasty king Den.

Name: Sematawytefnakht
Comment: Witnessed the conquest of Egypt by the hands of Alexander the Great.

Name: Semenkare
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th Dynasty.

Name: Semenre
Comment: A 16th dynasty Theban king during the Second Intermediate Period of Egypt who succeeded Nebiriau II.

Name: Semerkhet
Comment: A king during Egypt's 1st dynasty.

Name: Semqen
Comment: Early Hyksos ruler.

Name: Senakhtenre Ahmose
Comment: Pharaoh of the late 17th dynasty, his existence and complete name were confirmed by recent archeological discoveries.

Name: Seneb
Comment: Seneb was a dwarf who served as a high-ranking court official in the Old Kingdom.

Name: Senebhenaf
Comment: A vizier during the 13th dynasty of the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Senebi
Date: fl. c. mid-18th to early-17th century BC
Comment: A treasurer under the 13th dynasty Egyptian kings Neferhotep I and Sobekhotep IV.

Name: Senebkay
Comment: Obscur pharaoh whose tomb discovered in 2014 in Abydos might vindicate the existence of the Abydos Dynasty during the mid second intermediate period.

Name: Senedj
Comment: A king during the 2nd dynasty of Egypt who resided at Memphis.

Name: Senedjemib Inti
Comment: A vizier, who served king Djedkare Isesi.

Name: Senedjemib Mehi
Comment: A vizier who started out his career under king Djedkare Isesi and eventually became vizier under king Unas.

Name: Senenmut
Comment: An architect and government official. Senenmut entered royal service during the reign of Thutmose I or Thutmose II. After Hatshepsut became pharaoh, Senenmut became high steward.

Name: Senewosret-Ankh
Comment: He is known from a number of sources making it possible to reconstruct his career.

Name: Senkamanisken
Comment: A Nubian king based at Napata (reigned c. 640 BC – c. 620 BC). He was married to Queen Nasalsa who bore him two sons: Anlamani and Aspelta.

Name: Sennedjem
Comment: An Egyptian artisan who lived in Deir el-Medina near Thebes during the reigns of the 19th dynasty pharaohs Seti I and Ramesses II. He worked on the excavation and decoration of the nearby royal tombs.

Name: Sennefer
Comment: Mayor of Thebes and "Overseer of the Granaries and Fields, Gardens and Cattle of Amun" during the reign of Amenhotep II. He was a son of Ahmose Humay, brother to Amenhotep II's vizier Amenemopet.

Name: Sennefer
Date: fl. c. early to mid-15th century BC
Comment: A long serving Egyptian official under pharaohs Thutmose II, Hatshepsut, and Thutmose III. His titles included "Overseer of the Seal" and "Overseer of the Gold-land of Amun".

Name: Senneferi
Comment: Overseer of the Seal and "Overseer of the Gold-Land of Amun", during the reign of Thutmose III of the Egyptian 18th dynasty.

Name: Senseneb
Comment: The mother of pharaoh Thutmose I.

Name: Senusret
Comment: An Egyptian official who was a vizier during the last years of king Senusret I's rule and in the first years of king Amenemhet II.

Name: Senusret I
Comment: Son of Amenemhat I and Neferitatjenen. He continued his father's aggressive expansionist policies against Nubia. Senusret I established diplomatic relations with rulers in Syria and Canaan. He also tried to centralize the country's political structure by supporting nomarchs who were loyal to him. Also referred to as Sesostris I and Senwosret I.

Name: Senusret II
Comment: Son of Amenemhat II. His pyramid was constructed at El-Lahun. Senusret II was interested in the Faiyum oasis region and began work on an extensive irrigation system. Senusret II maintained good relations with the various nomarchs of Egypt. Also referred to as Sesostris II and Senwosret II.

Name: Senusret III
Comment: Son of Senusret II and Khnemetneferhedjet I. He built the Sesostris Canal and expanded Egyptian control deep into Nubia. His military campaigns gave rise to an era of peace and economic prosperity and he reduced the power of the nomarchs. Also referred to as Sesostris III and Senwosret III.

Name: Senusret IV
Date: fl. c. late-17th to early-16th century BC
Comment: Pharaoh of some parts of Upper Egypt during the second intermediate period when the Hyksos controlled Lower Egypt.

Name: Seqenenre Tao
Comment: He probably was the son and successor to Senaktenre Ahmose and Queen Tetisheri.

Name: Serethor
Comment: Serethor was likely a wife of king Den.

Name: Serfka
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu, and Itet.

Name: Seshemetka
Comment: Possibly a wife of king Den and the mother of Anedjib.

Name: Sesheshet
Comment: The mother of pharaoh Teti. She was instrumental in enabling her son to gain the throne and reconciling two warring factions of the royal family. Also known as Shesh.

Name: Setau
Comment: Setau was the Viceroy of Kush in the second half of Ramesses II's reign.

Name: Setepenre
Comment: A daughter of Pharaoh Akhenaten and queen Nefertiti.

Name: Seth Meribre
Comment: Poorly known king of the 13th dynasty reigning in the early second intermediate period.

Name: Seth-Peribsen
Comment: A king during the 2nd dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Seti
Comment: An Egyptian soldier during the late 18th dynasty, the commander of the army and later vizier. He was the father of Pharaoh Ramesses I. Also known as Suti.

Name: Seti
Comment: The Viceroy of Kush Seti is attested in year 1 of Siptah. Seti is also mentioned on some monuments of his son Amenemhab. Amenemhab was the son of Seti and the Lady Amenemtaiauw. Seti held the titles fan-bearer on the king's right, king's scribe of the letters of the Pharaoh.

Name: Seti I Menmaatre
Comment: The son of Ramesses I and Queen Sitre, and the father of Ramesses II. He reconquered most of the territories in Canaan and Syria disputed with the Hittites. Seti I also fought a series of wars in Libya and Nubia. Also referred to as Sethos I.

Name: Seti II Userkheperure Setepenre
Comment: He was the son of Merneptah and queen Isetnofret II. Seti II had to deal with the accession of a rival named Amenmesse who seized control over Thebes and Nubia in Upper Egypt. Also referred to as Sethos II.

Name: Seti-Merenptah
Comment: An Egyptian prince of the late 19th dynasty, a son of Pharaoh Seti II and Isetnofret II.

Name: Setnakhte Userkhaure-Setepenre
Comment: The first pharaoh of the 20th dynasty of Egypt (reigned c. 1190 BC – c. 1186 BC) and the father of Ramesses III. He was either an usurper who seized the throne or a member of a minor line of the royal family who emerged as pharaoh.

Name: Setut
Comment: A pharaoh of the Herakleopolite 9th dynasty, also called Senen ... .

Name: Seuserenre Bebiankh
Comment: see Bebiankh

Name: Sewadjkare
Comment: A pharaoh of the 13th dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Sewadjkare Hori
Comment: A pharaoh of the 13th dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Sewadjkare III
Comment: Pharaoh of the 14th dynasty, probably of Canaanite descent and reigning over the eastern Nile Delta during the second intermediate period.

Name: Shabaka Neferkare
Comment: Shabaka is thought to be the son of King Kashta and Pebatjma, although a text from the time of Taharqa could be interpreted to mean that Shabaka was a brother of Taharqa and hence a son of Piye. He consolidated the Nubia's control over Egypt from Nubia to the Delta region. Shabaka maintained Egypt's independence from the Assyrian empire under Sargon II.

Name: Sharek
Date: reigned during the Second Intermediate Period
Comment: He was possibly the same person of the Manethonian Salitis, founder of the 15th Dynasty.

Name: Shebitku
Comment: He was the nephew and successor of Shabaka and a son of Piye, the founder of the dynasty. Shebitku actively resisted Assyrian expansion under Sennacherib into Canaan.

Name: Shedsu-nefertum
Comment: Shedsunefertem was the son of the High Priest Ankhefensekhmet and the lady Tapeshenese, who was First Chief of the Harem of Ptah and Prophetess of Mut.

Name: Shemay
Comment: Shemay was nomarch of Coptos and vizier of Upper Egypt in the early First Intermediate Period. The beneficiary of most of the Coptos Decrees, his career is symptomatic of the decline of kingship at the end of the Old Kingdom.

Name: Sheneh
Comment: Semitic ruler of Lower Egypt belonging to the 14th dynasty or vassal of the Hyksos and belonging to the 16th dynasty during the second intermediate period.

Name: Shenshek
Comment: Semitic ruler of Lower Egypt belonging to the 14th dynasty or vassal of the Hyksos and belonging to the 16th dynasty during the second intermediate period.

Name: Shepenupet I
Comment: She was the first Divine Adoratrice of Amun to wield political power in Thebes. She was a daughter of Osorkon III and Queen Karoadjet. Also called Shepenwpet I.

Name: Shepenupet II
Comment: She was the daughter of the first Kushite pharaoh Piye and sister of Piye's successors Taharqa and Shabaka. Also called Shepenwpet II.

Name: Shepseska
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu, and Itet.

Name: Shepseskaf
Comment: Possibly a son of the Egyptian king Menkaure who succeeded his father on the throne (reigned c. 2503 BC – c. 2498 BC). He was probably the last king of the 4th dynasty.

Name: Shepseskare Isi
Comment: He reigned c. 2467 BC – c. 2460 BC. Sometime referred to as Shepseskare, Sisiris.

Name: Shepsesneb
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Shepset-ipet
Comment: Daughter of a king of the late 2nd Dynasty, possibly Khasekhemwy or Peribsen.

Name: Shery
Comment: An Egyptian official who probably lived during the 4th Dynasty. He was Great of the Ten of Upper Egypt and Chief of the wab-priest of Peribsen in the necropolis of Senedj.

Name: Sheshi Maaibre
Comment: A 14th dynasty pharaoh of Egypt during the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Shoshenq I Hedjkheperre Setepenre
Comment: He was a Meshwesh (Libyan) Berber king of Egypt and the founder of the 22nd Dynasty. He was the son of Nimlot, Great Chief of the Ma, and his wife Tentshepeh. Sheshonk I pursued an aggressive foreign policy against Syria, Philistine, Phoenicia, Judah and Israel. Also known as Shoshenq I, Sheshonk, Sheshonq I.

Name: Sheshonk II Heqakheperre
Comment: A king of the 22nd dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Shoshenq III Usermaatre Setepenre
Comment: His reign was marked by the loss of Egypt's political unity, with the appearance of Pedubast I at Thebes. Henceforth, the 22nd Dynasty kings only controlled Lower Egypt.

Name: Shoshenq IV Hedjkheperre Setepenre
Comment: A king during Egypt's 22nd dynasty. Also referred to as Shoshenq IV.

Name: Shoshenq V
Comment: The final king of the 22nd dynasty of Egypt of Meshwesh Libyans which controlled Lower Egypt. With his death, the kingdom in the Egyptian Delta disintegrated into various city states.

Name: Shoshenq VI
Comment: A 23rd Dynasty king based at Thebes (reigned c. 804 BC – c. 798 BC). He was defeated and ousted from power by Prince Osorkon (later Osorkon III).

Name: Shoshenq
Comment: A Great chief of the Ma during the 21st dynasty, father of pharaoh Osorkon the Elder and grandfather of pharaoh Shoshenq I.

Name: Shoshenq
Comment: The eldest son of pharaoh Osorkon I and queen Maatkare, the daughter of Psusennes II, and served as the High Priest of Amun at Thebes during his father's reign.

Name: Shoshenq
Comment: Shoshenq was the eldest son of Osorkon II and Queen Karomama.

Name: Siamun Netjerkheperre-Setepenamun
Comment: Siamun doubled the size of the Temple of Amun at Tanis and initiated works at the Temple of Horus at Mesen. He embarked upon an active foreign policy.

Name: Siamun
Comment: He was the son of Pharaoh Ahmose I and Queen Ahmose Nefertari.

Name: Siamun
Comment: A son of Pharaoh Thutmose III.

Name: Siaspiqa
Comment: A Kushite King of Meroe (reigned c. 487 BC – c. 468 BC).

Name: Siatum
Comment: He was probably one of the sons of Pharaoh Thutmose IV and thus the brother or half-brother of Amenhotep III.

Name: Siese
Comment: An Egyptian vizier and treasurer during the 12th dynasty. He was probably vizier under pharaoh Amenemhat II. Also called Zaaset.

Name: Sihathor
Comment: Ephemeral coregent of his brother Neferhotep I.

Name: Simut
Comment: An Egyptian priest who held the position of Second Prophet of Amun towards the end of the reign of the 18th dynasty Pharaoh Amenhotep III. Simut was also treasurer (“Overseer of the House of Silver”) and “sealer of every contract in Karnak”.

Name: Siptah Akhenre Setepenre
Date: fl. c. late-13th to early-12th century BC
Comment: His father's identity is unknown with both Seti II and Amenmesse being suggested. Siptah succeeded to the throne as a child after the death of Seti II. Also known as Merneptah Siptah.

Name: Sitamun
Comment: She was the eldest daughter of Pharaoh Amenhotep III and his wife Tiye and later married her father.

Name: Sitdjehuti
Comment: She was a daughter of Pharaoh Senakhtenre Ahmose and the sister to Pharaoh Seqenenre Tao and the queens Ahhotep and Ahmose Inhapy. She was married to her (half-)brother Tao.

Name: Sithathoriunet
Comment: She was possibly a daughter of Senusret II.

Name: Sitre
Comment: Wife of Pharaoh Ramesses I of Egypt and mother of Seti I. Also called Tia-Sitre.

Name: Sitre In
Comment: The nurse of the female pharaoh Hatshepsut.

Name: Smendes Hedjkheperre Setepenre
Date: fl. c. early to mid-11th century BC
Comment: The first pharaoh of the 21st dynasty of Egypt (reigned c. 1077 BC – c. 1052 BC). He is thought to have been a powerful governor in Lower Egypt during the reign of Ramesses XI.

Name: Smendes II
Comment: He was a son of High Priest Menkheperre and Princess Isetemkheb, the daughter of Psusennes I. Also known as Nesbanebdjed II.

Name: Smendes III
Comment: A son of pharaoh Osorkon I, he officiated under the reign of the brother Takelot I. Also known as Nesbanebdjed III.

Name: Smenkhkare
Comment: He was probably a younger son of Amenhotep III and queen Tiye, and therefore a younger brother of Akhenaten.

Name: Snaaib
Comment: Poorly known pharaoh of the late 13th or Abydos dynasty during the second intermediate period, close to the time of the Hyksos invasion.

Name: Sneferu
Comment: He built at least three pyramids at Dahshur (including the Bent Pyramid and the Red Pyramid) and Meidum (Meidum pyramid). He introduced major innovations in the design and construction of pyramids. Also known as Snefru, Snofru or Soris.

Name: Sneferukhaf
Comment: He was a son of Prince Nefermaat II and a grandson of Princess Nefertkau.

Name: Sobekemhat
Comment: An Egyptian vizier under king Senusret III during the 12th dynasty.

Name: Sobekemsaf I
Comment: Sekhemre Shedtawy Sobekemsaf reigned during the Second Intermediate Period. Sobekemsaf I is thought to have been the father of both Intef VI and Intef VII.

Name: Sobekemsaf II Sekhemrewadjkhaw
Comment: He may have reigned after Djehuti and Intef VI. Sobekemsaf's chief wife was Queen Nubemhet.

Name: Sobekhotep I Sekhemrekhutawy
Comment: First pharaoh of the 13th dynasty, possibly a son of Amenemhat IV, otherwise, may have reigned later in the dynasty.

Name: Sobekhotep II
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th Dynasty. He appears in the Turin King List as Sobekhotep and is otherwise mainly known from reliefs coming from a chapel set up in Abydos, from a pedestal of a statue and from a fragment of a column.

Name: Sobekhotep III Sekhemresewdjtawy
Comment: His father was Mentuhotep. His mother was Jewetibaw. The king had two wives, Senebhenas and Neni.

Name: Sobekhotep IV Khaneferre
Comment: He was the son of Haankhef and Kemi. His brother, Neferhotep I, was his predecessor on the throne.

Name: Sobekhotep V
Comment: Sobekhotep Merhotepre was an Egyptian king.

Name: Sobekhotep VI
Comment: Sobekhotep Khahotepre was an Egyptian king.

Name: Merkawre Sobekhotep VII
Comment: Among the last pharaohs of the 13th dynasty, shortly before the Hyksos conquest of Lower Egypt.

Name: Sobekhotep VIII Sekhemre Susertawi
Comment: He is believed to be the successor of Djehuti. He reigned over Upper Egypt during the time of the Hyksos conquest of Memphis and Lower Egypt.

Name: Sobeknakht II
Comment: A local governor at El-Kab and a supporter of the Theban 16th dynasty during the Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Sobekneferu
Comment: She was a daughter of Pharaoh Amenemhat III. Also known as Neferusobek.

Name: Sonbef
Comment: Second pharaoh of the 13th dynasty, possibly a son of Amenemhat IV. Also known as Amenemhat Sonbef.

Name: Sosibius
Comment: The chief minister of Ptolemy IV Philopator. He was able to exercise great power through his influence over the king throughout Ptolemy IV's reign. Based on Sosibius' advice, Ptolemy IV put to death his uncle Lysimachus, his brother Magas, and his mother Berenice.

Name: Sosibius of Tarentum
Comment: One of the captains of the body-guards of Ptolemy II Philadelphus, king of Egypt. He may have been the father of the Sosibius, chief minister to Ptolemy IV Philopator.

Name: Tabekenamun
Comment: Tabekenamun was a daughter of King Piye and may have been a queen consort to her brother Taharqa or to Shabaka.

Name: Tabiry
Comment: Tabiry was the daughter of Alara of Nubia and his wife Kasaqa and the wife of King Piye.

Name: Tadibast III
Comment: Tadibast III was the mother of Osorkon IV and likely the wife of Shoshenq V.

Name: Tadukhipa
Comment: A daughter of Tushratta, king of Mitanni and his queen, Juni. Tushratta married his daughter to his ally pharaoh Amenhotep III to cement their two states' alliances. Amenhotep III died shortly after Tadukhipa arrived in Egypt so she eventually married his son and heir Akhenaten. Her name is sometime written as Tadu-Hepa.

Name: Taharqa
Comment: He was the son of Piye, the Nubian king of Napata who had first conquered Egypt. During his reign, Assyria forces under General Esarhaddon invaded Egypt and managed to conquer Lower Egypt putting Neto I on the throne in Sias.

Name: Takahatenamun
Comment: She was the daughter of King Piye and the sister-wife of King Taharqa.

Name: Takelot I Hedjkheperre Setepenre
Comment: He was a son of Osorkon I and Queen Tashedkhonsu. He married Kapes who bore him a son, Osorkon II. Takelot I's authority was not fully recognised in Upper Egypt where a local Theban king challenged his authority.

Name: Takelot II Si-Ese Hedjkheperre Setepenre
Comment: A Pharaoh and High Priest of Amun, ruling Middle and Upper Egypt separately from the Tanite 22nd dynasty kings who at that time only controlled Lower Egypt.

Name: Takelot III Si-Ese Usimare Setepenamun
Comment: He was Osorkon III's eldest son and successor and High Priest of Amun at Thebes.

Name: Takhat
Comment: The mother of the usurper pharaoh Amenmesse. She was a queen consort to either Merenptah or Seti II.

Name: Takhat
Comment: The mother of pharaoh Ramesses IX and probably the wife of Montuherkhepeshef, a son of Ramesses III.

Name: Takhuit
Comment: Takhuit was the wife of Psamtik II and the mother of Pharaoh Apries and the God's Wife of Amun Ankhnesneferibre.

Name: Talakhamani
Comment: A Kushite King of Meroe (reigned c. 435 BC – c. 431 BC). He may have been a son of Nasakhma and a younger brother of Malewiebamani. It is also possible Talakhamani was a son of Malewiebamani.

Name: Tantamani
Comment: After the Assyrians had appointed Necho I as king and left Egypt, Tantamani marched from Nubia, killed Necho I in battle and reoccupied all of Egypt. The Assyrians returned to Egypt defeated Tantamani's army and effectively ended Nubian control over Egypt. Also known as Tandaname, Tanwetamani or Tementhes.

Name: Seqenenre Tao
Comment: Ruled over the local kingdoms of the Theban region of Egypt in the 17th dynasty (reigned c. 1558 BC – c. 1554 BC) . He probably was the son and successor to Senaktenre Ahmose and Queen Tetisheri. Also known as Sekenenra Taa.

Name: Tashedkhonsu
Comment: Wife of Pharaoh Osorkon I and the mother of Pharaoh Takelot I.

Name: Tawerettenru
Comment: The Royal Wife of Ramesses V.

Name: Tefibi
Comment: Nomarch of Asyut, he helped an Herakleopolite pharaoh of the 10th dynasty in the reconquest of Thinis.

Name: Tefnakht Shepsesre
Comment: A Libyan-descended prince of Sais, Great Chief of the Meshwesh and Great Chief of the Libu, and founder of the 24th dynasty of Egypt. Tefnakht established his capital at Sais and was able to unify many of the cities of the Delta region. Also known as Tnephachthos.

Name: Tefnakht II
Comment: A native king who ruled Sais during the 25th Nubian Dynasty of Egypt.

Name: Tentamun
Comment: A daughter of Thutmose IV.

Name: Tentamun
Comment: Probably the wife of Ramesses XI, last ruler of the 20th dynasty.

Name: Tentamun
Comment: The wife of the 21st dynasty pharaoh Smendes. She was probably the daughter of Ramesses XI, last ruler of the 20th dynasty.

Name: Tentkheta
Comment: Wife of Amasis II. She was a daughter of a priest of Ptah named Padineith. She was the mother of Pharaoh Psamtik III. Also known as Tanetkheta

Name: Teos
Comment: A 30th dynasty pharaoh of Egypt (reigned 362 BC – 360 BC) who was overthrown by Nectanebo II with the aid of Agesilaus II of Sparta and was forced to flee to Persia. The Persian king Artaxerxes II gave him refuge and Teos lived in Persian exile until his death.

Name: Teta
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu, and Itet.

Name: Teti
Comment: The first pharaoh of the 6th dynasty of Egypt. Teti was either murdered by his palace bodyguards in a harem plot or assassinated by the usurper Userkare. Also known by the name Othoes.

Name: Teti, Son of Minhotep
Comment: An Egyptian official in Coptos during the reign of the Seventeenth Dynasty Pharaoh, Nubkheperre Intef. Known from the Coptos Decree, which deprives him of his office and its stipend for some act of sacrilege.

Name: Tetisheri
Comment: Wife of pharaoh Senakhtenre Ahmose and the mother of Seqenenre Tao, Queen Ahhotep I and possibly Kamose.

Name: Tey
Comment: The wife of Kheperkheprure Ay who was a pharaoh of Egypt's 18th dynasty.

Name: Thamphthis
Comment: The Greek name of an Egyptian king of the 4th dynasty. His original Egyptian name is lost, but it may have been Djedefptah or Ptahdjedef.

Name: Thutmose I
Comment: During his reign, he campaigned deep into the Levant and Nubia, pushing the borders of Egypt further than ever before. He built many temples throughout Egypt and was the first pharaoh to build a tomb for himself in the Valley of the Kings. His name is sometimes written as Thothmes, Thutmosis or Tuthmosis I.

Name: Thutmose II
Comment: Son of Thutmose I and Queen Mutnofret. He built some minor monuments and initiated some minor campaigns. Thutmose II was probably strongly influenced by his wife and royal half-sister Hatshepsut.

Name: Thutmose III
Comment: During the early years of his reign, he was co-regent with his stepmother, Hatshepsut, who was named the pharaoh. After her death, he created the largest empire Egypt had ever seen. He conducted at least seventeen campaigns and he conquered lands from northern Syria to the fourth cataract of the Nile.

Name: Thutmose IV
Comment: Son of Amenhotep II and Tiaa. Known for the restoration of the Sphinx at Giza.

Name: Thutmose
Comment: The eldest son of pharaoh Amenhotep III and Queen Tiye. His apparent early death led to Akhenaten becoming the successor to Amenhotep III. Also known as Djhutmose.

Name: Thutmose
Comment: The official court sculptor of the Egyptian Pharaoh Akhenaten in the latter part of his reign. Also known as Djhutmose or Thutmosis

Name: Thutmose
Comment: Vizier during the reign of Amenhotep III, was the father of Ptahmose.

Name: Thutmose
Comment: Vizier during the latter part of the reign of Ramesses II.

Name: Tia
Comment: The daughter of Pharaoh Seti I and Queen Tuya and the elder sister of Ramesses II. Married to a noble man also called Tia. Buried with her husband in Saqqara.

Name: Tiaa
Comment: She was the wife of Pharaoh Amenhotep II and the mother of Thutmose IV.

Name: Tiaa
Comment: She was a daughter of Pharaoh Thutmose IV.

Name: Tiaa
Comment: Possibly a wife of Pharaoh Seti II.

Name: Tiye
Date: fl. c. early to mid-14th century BC
Comment: The daughter of Yuya and Tjuyu. She was the Great Royal Wife of pharaoh Amenhotep III and matriarch of the Amarna family from which many members of the royal family of Ancient Egypt were to come.

Name: Tiye
Comment: A wife of Ramesses III. She instigated a failed "harem conspiracy" to kill the king and place Tiye's son Pentawer on the throne, instead of the appointed heir, who was the son of queen Iset Ta-Hemdjert.

Name: Tiy-Merenese
Comment: The wife of Setnakhte and mother of Ramesses III. Her name is sometimes written as Teye-Merenaset or Tiye-Mereniset.

Name: Tjahapimu
Comment: A prince, regent of Egypt during the reign of his brother Teos, and father of the future pharaoh Nectanebo II.

Name: Tjanefer
Comment: A 21st dynasty Egyptian priest. His father was Nesipaherenmut, the Fourth Prophet of Amun, his mother was Isetemheb. He married Gautseshen, the daughter of High Priest Menkheperre and Princess Isetemkheb.

Name: Tjuyu
Comment: An Egyptian noblewoman and the mother of queen Tiye, wife of pharaoh Amenhotep III. Also known as Thuya, Thuyu and Tuya.

Name: Tlepolemus
Comment: Regent of Egypt during the reign of the boy king Ptolemy V. Tlepolemus was military governor of Pelusium when the regent Agathocles and his family were overthrown and killed in a popular uprising. Tlepolemus briefly took Agathocles' place as regent until he was replaced by Aristomenes of Alyzia.

Name: Tryphaena
Comment: A Ptolemaic princess and Seleucid queen. She was the oldest daughter of the Egyptian king Ptolemy VIII and Cleopatra III. She married the Seleucid king Antiochus VIII Grypus and was queen of Syria (124 BC – 111 BC).

Name: Tutankhamun
Comment: Tutankhamen reigned c. 1333 BC – c. 1323 BC. He married his half sister, Ankhesenpaaten, who later changed her name to Ankhesenamun. He ended the worship of the god, Aten and restored the god Amun to supremacy. The capital of Egypt was moved back to Thebes.

Name: Tutkheperre Shoshenq
Comment: A 22nd dynasty Libyan king of Egypt.

Name: Tutu
Comment: Tutu, the Egyptian official, was one of pharaoh's officials during the Amarna letters period.

Name: Tuya
Comment: The wife of Pharaoh Seti I and mother of Ramesses II. Also known as Tuy and Mut-Tuya.

Name: Twosret
Comment: The last pharaoh of the 19th Dynasty of Egypt. She was a royal wife of Seti II. She was regent to Seti's heir Siptah. When Siptah died, Twosret officially assumed the throne. Twosret's reign ended in a civil war leading to her successor Setnakhte founding the 20th dynasty. Also known as Tawosret and Tausret.

Name: Tyti
Comment: An Egyptian queen of the 20th dynasty. She may have been married to Ramesses X.

Name: Udjahorresnet
Comment: A high official who made a remarkable career under Cambyses II and Darius I during the first Persian domination (27th dynasty).

Name: Udjebten
Comment: A wife of Pharaoh Pepi II. Her name is also written as Wadjebten.

Name: Unas
Comment: The last 5th dynasty pharaoh of Egypt. Unas may have had two queen consorts, Khenut and Nebit. His name is also written as Oenas, Unis, Wenis, or Ounas.

Name: Useramen
Comment: A vizier of Egypt under Hatshepsut and Tuthmosis III. Also known as User and Amenuser.

Name: Userhet
Main Title: Overseer of the Fields of Amun
Comment: Userhet was buried in the Valley of the Kings, in tomb KV45. He probably lived during the rule of Thutmose IV.

Name: Userkaf
Comment: The first 5th dynasty king of Egypt. He started the tradition of building sun temples at Abusir. He constructed the Pyramid of Userkaf complex at Saqqara.

Name: Userkare
Comment: He is considered to be either a usurper to the throne after Teti or he could have been a son of Teti and Queen Khuit.

Name: Usermontu
Comment: He served during the reign of Pharaoh Tutankhamun.

Name: Wadjmose
Comment: A son of Pharaoh Thutmose I.

Name: Wadjitefni
Comment: A son of a king of the early 2nd Dynasty.

Name: Wahibre Ibiau
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th Dynasty.

Name: Wahkare Khety
Comment: A pharaoh likely of the 10th dynasty of Egypt controlling territories based around Herakleopolis.

Name: Wahtye
Comment: A high-ranking priest and official whose tomb was uncovered in 2018 in the Saqqara necropolis and was the subject of the Netflix documentary Secrets of the Saqqara Tomb.

Name: Webensenu
Comment: He was a son of Pharaoh Amenhotep II.

Name: Wegaf Khutawyre
Comment: An Egyptian king of the 13th Dynasty, also known as Ugaf.

Name: Wehemka
Comment: A son of Nefermaat, the eldest son of pharaoh Sneferu and Itet.

Name: Wendjebauendjed
Comment: A general, high official and priest under pharaoh Psusennes I, known for his undisturbed tomb and its relative treasure at Tanis.

Name: Weneg
Comment: Weneg was the royal Nebti name of a pharaoh during the 2nd dynasty of Egypt. He is assumed to have been a king who ruled Egypt between Nynetjer and Khasekhemwy. He is also referred to as Wneg or Wadjnes or Tlas.

Name: Wenennefer
Comment: A High Priest of Osiris under pharaoh Ramesses II.

Name: Weni the Elder
Date: fl. c. late 24th to early 23rd centuries BC
Comment: A court official of the 6th dynasty of Egypt. He began his career under Teti, and served as a general under Pepi I Meryre and as governor of Upper Egypt during the reign of Merenre Nemtyemsaf I.

Name: Wentawat
Comment: Wentawat (also written as Wentawuat), was Viceroy of Kush under Ramesses IX. Wentawat was possibly a son of the Viceroy Hori II

Name: Wepwawetemsaf
Comment: Poorly known pharaoh during the second intermediate period.

Name: Wetka
Comment: Wetka was a son of Prince Khufukhaf I and Nefertkau II, and a grandson of Khufu.

Name: Wazad
Comment: Pharaoh of Canaanite descent reigning over the eastern Nile Delta during the second intermediate period.

Name: Ya'ammu
Comment: Possibly, an early semitic pharaoh of the eastern Nile Delta during the second intermediate period. Alternatively a vassal of the Hyksos kings.

Name: Yakareb
Comment: Semitic pharaoh of the eastern Nile Delta during the second intermediate period.

Name: Yakbim
Comment: Possibly, an early semitic pharaoh of the eastern Nile Delta during the second intermediate period. Alternatively a vassal of the Hyksos kings.

Name: Yanhamu
Comment: An Egyptian commissioner mentioned in the 1350-1335 BC Amarna letters correspondence. His name has also been read as Yenhamu, and Enhamu.

Name: Yaqub-Har
Comment: Either a pharaoh of the 14th dynasty reigning over the eastern Nile Delta or a vassal of the Hyksos kings during Egypt's fragmented Second Intermediate Period.

Name: Yuny
Date: fl. c. early to mid-13th century BC
Comment: An official during the reign of pharaoh Ramesses II. He served as chief scribe of the court, the overseer of priests and royal steward. Yuni started building projects at Amara West and Aksha. His name is sometimes written as Iuny.

Name: Yuya
Comment: An Egyptian courtier of the 18th dynasty of Egypt. He was the King's Lieutenant and Master of the Horse. He married Tjuyu who held high offices in governmental and religious hierarchies. Their daughter, Tiye, became queen to Amenhotep III. His name is sometimes written as Iouiya.

Name: Yuyu
Comment: A High Priest of Osiris under Ramesses II and Merenptah, and a grandson of Wenennefer.

Name: Zamonth
Comment: Also known as Samonth. An Ancient Egyptian vizier who was in office at the end of the Twelfth Dynasty

Name: Zannanza
Comment: Prince Zannanza (died c. 1324 BC) was a son of Suppiluliuma I, king of the Hittites. He is best known for almost becoming the Pharaoh of Egypt and because his death caused a diplomatic incident between the Hittite Empire and Egypt, that resulted in warfare.

Name: Zoser
Comment: See Djoser
